# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mains-electricity
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] An **AC adapter** or **AC/DC adapter** (also called a **wall charger**, **power adapter**, or informally **wall wart**, or, in some configurations, **power brick**) is a type of external power supply, often enclosed in a case similar to an AC plug.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] AC adapters deliver electric power to devices that lack internal components to draw voltage and power from mains power themselves.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] The internal circuitry of an external power supply is often very similar to the design that would be used for a built-in or internal supply.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] When used with battery-powered equipment, adapters typically charge the battery as well as powering the equipment.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Aside from obviating the need for internal power supplies, adapters offer flexibility: a device can draw power from 120 VAC or 230 VAC mains, vehicle battery, or aircraft battery, just by using different adapters.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Safety can be another advantage, as hazardous 120 or 240 volt mains power is transformed to a lower, safer voltage at the wall outlet before going into the appliance handled by the user.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Size and weight of the device was largely determined by the transformer, which in turn was determined by the power output and mains frequency.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Ratings over a few watts made the devices too large and heavy to be physically supported by a wall outlet.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] The output voltage of these adapters varied with load; for equipment requiring a more stable voltage, linear voltage regulator circuitry was added.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Losses in the transformer and the linear regulator were considerable; efficiency was relatively low, and significant power dissipated as heat even when not driving a load.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Early in the twenty-first century, switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) became almost ubiquitous for this purpose due to their compact size and light weight relative to their power output ability.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Mains voltage is rectified to a high direct voltage driving a switching circuit, which contains a transformer operating at a high frequency and outputs direct current at the desired voltage.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] The high-frequency ripple is more easily filtered out than mains-frequency.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] The high frequency allows the transformer to be small, which reduces its losses; and the switching regulator can be much more efficient than a linear regulator.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] The result is a much more efficient, smaller, and lighter device.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Safety is ensured, as in the older linear circuit, because a transformer still provides galvanic isolation.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Many inexpensive switched-mode AC adapters do not implement adequate filtering and/or shielding for electromagnetic interference that they generate.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] The nature of these high speed, high-energy switching designs is such that when these preventative measures are not implemented, relatively high energy harmonics can be generated, and radiated, well into the radio portion of the spectrum.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] The amount of RF energy typically decreases with frequency; so, for instance, interference in the medium wave (US AM) broadcast band in the one megahertz region may be strong, while interference with the FM broadcast band around 100 megahertz may be considerably less.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Distance is a factor; the closer the interference is to a radio receiver, the more intense it will be.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Even WiFi reception in the gigahertz range can be degraded if the receiving antennae are very close to a radiating AC adapter.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] A determination of if interference is coming from a specific AC adapter can be made simply by unplugging the suspect adapter while observing the amount of interference received in the problem radio band.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] In a modern household or business environment, there may be multiple AC adapters in use; in such a case, unplug them all, then plug them back in one by one until the culprit or culprits is found.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Traditionally, wall adapters provided a constant voltage.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Later, battery charging protocols such as Quick Charge by Qualcomm and USB Power Delivery started allowing charged devices to request different voltages suited for their needs, usually higher voltages to increase power without adding heat to the copper wires of the USB cable.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] In the past, "SuperCharge" by Huawei and "Dash Charge" by OnePlus did the opposite, requesting a slightly lowered voltage to directly match the battery voltage inside the smartphone so no change of voltage has to take place inside the phone, leading to less heating up.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] This required special USB cables with thicker copper wires.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] In the early 2020s, the use of gallium nitride instead of silicon in switching wall adapters bumped up their output power at the same physical size, making compact wall warts able to power even some laptops, not only smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] The creation of Gallium Nitride chargers was delayed owing to their excessive costs and that fast charging technology was less in demand than it has become after 2020.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] External AC adapters are widely used to power small or portable electronic devices.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] A survey of consumers showed widespread dissatisfaction with the cost, inconvenience, and wastefulness of the profusion of power adapters used by electronic devices.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] The issue of inefficiency of some power supplies has become well known, with U.S. president George W.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Bush referring in 2001 to such devices as "energy vampires".
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Legislation is being enacted in the EU and a number of U.S. states to reduce the level of energy wasted by some of these devices.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Such initiatives include standby power and the One Watt Initiative.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] But others have argued that these inefficient devices are low-powered, e.g., devices that are used for small battery chargers, so even if they have a low efficiency, the amount of energy they waste is less than 1% of household consumption of electric energy.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Considering the total efficiency of power supplies for small electronic equipment, the older mains-frequency linear transformer-based power supply was found in a 2002 report to have efficiencies from 20 to 75%, and have considerable energy loss even when powered up but not supplying power.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) are much more efficient; a good design can be 80–90% efficient, and is also much smaller and lighter.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] In 2002 most external plug-in "wall wart" power adapters commonly used for low-power consumer electronics devices were of linear design, as well as supplies built into some equipment.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] External supplies are usually left plugged in even when not in use, and consume from a few watts to 35 watts of power in that state.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Since the report was published, SMPSs have indeed replaced linear supplies to a great extent, even in wall warts.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] The 2002 report estimated that 6% of electrical energy used in the U.S.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] "flows through" power supplies (not counting only the wall warts).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] The website where the report was published said in 2010 that despite the spread of SMPSs, "today's power supplies consume at least 2% of all U.S. electricity production.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] More efficient power supply designs could cut that usage in half".
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Since wasted electrical energy is released as heat, an inefficient power supply is hot to the touch, as is one that wastes power without an electrical load.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] This waste heat is itself a problem in warm weather, since it may require additional air conditioning to prevent overheating, and even to remove the unwanted heat from large supplies.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] External power adapters can fail, or can become separated from the product they are intended to power.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Consequently, there is a market for replacement adapters.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] The replacement must match input and output voltages, match or exceed current capability, and be fitted with a matching connector.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Many electrical products are poorly labeled with information concerning the power supply they require, so it is prudent to record the specifications of the original power supply in advance, to ease replacement if the original is later lost.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Careful labeling of power adapters can also reduce the likelihood of a mixup which could cause equipment damage.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Some "universal" replacement power supplies allow output voltage and polarity to be switched to match a range of equipment.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] With the advent of switch-mode supplies, adapters which can work with any voltage from 110 VAC to 240 VAC became widely available; previously either 100–120 VAC or 200–240 VAC versions were used.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Adapters which can also be used with motor vehicle and aircraft power *(see EmPower)* are available.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Four-way **X connectors** or six-way **star connectors**, also known as **spider connectors**, with multiple plug sizes and types are common on generic power supplies.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Other replacement power supplies have arrangements for changing the power connector, with four to nine different alternatives available when purchased in a set.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] This allows many different configurations of AC adapters to be put together, without requiring soldering.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Philmore and other competing brands offer similar AC adapters with interchangeable connectors.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] The label on a power supply may not be a reliable guide to the actual voltage it supplies under varying conditions.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Many low-cost power supplies are "unregulated", in that their voltage can change considerably with load.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] If they are lightly loaded, they may put out much more than the nominal "name plate" voltage, which could damage the load.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] If they are heavily loaded, the output voltage may droop appreciably, in some cases well below the nominal label voltage even within the nominal rated current, causing the equipment being supplied to malfunction or be damaged.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Supplies with linear (as against switched) regulators are heavy, bulky, and expensive.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Modern switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) are smaller, lighter, and more efficient.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] They put out a much more constant voltage than unregulated supplies as the input voltage and the load current vary.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] When introduced, their prices were high, but by the early 21st century the prices of switch-mode components had dropped to a degree which allowed even cheap supplies to use this technology, saving the cost of a larger and heavier mains-frequency transformer.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Some universal adapters automatically set their output voltage and maximum current according to which of a range of interchangeable tips is fitted; tips are available to fit and supply appropriate power to many notebook computers and mobile devices.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Different tips may use the same connector, but automatically supply different power; it is essential to use the right tip for the apparatus being powered, but no switch needs to be set correctly by the user.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] The advent of switch-mode power supplies has allowed adapters to work from any AC mains supply from 100 to 240 V with an appropriate plug; operation from standard 12 V DC vehicle and aircraft supplies can also be supported.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] With the appropriate adapter, accessories, and tips, a variety of equipment can be powered from almost any source of power.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] A battery eliminator is an adapter intended to allow a device intended for battery operation, such as a radio, to be operated from an AC outlet.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] All radios, except crystal sets, used inconvenient and messy vacuum tube batteries until the mid- to late-1920s.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Battery eliminators that plugged into light sockets became very popular.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Early commercial units were produced by the Edward S.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Rogers, Sr. company in 1925 as a complement to its line of batteryless radios.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Another early producer of battery eliminators was the Galvin Manufacturing Corporation (later known as Motorola), which was opened on September 25, 1928, by Paul Galvin and his brother Joseph E.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Eliminators became obsolete for radios after RCA introduced AC tubes in 1927, enabling receivers to plug into household power.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] The industry rapidly adopted AC tubes, and companies which launched exclusively manufacture that product such as Philco had to quickly pivot to radio manufacturing to remain relevant and existent.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] In early laptop computers, the power supply units were internal like in desktop computers.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] To facilitate portability by sparing physical space and reducing the weight, power supply units were externalized.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] When a laptop computer is operated while recharging, the integrated circuitry which controls the charging makes use of a power supply unit's remaining electrical current capacity.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] This allows supplying the device's components with power during usage while maintaining an uncompromised constant charging speed.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] The USB connector (and voltage) has emerged as a de facto standard in low-power AC adapters for many portable devices.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] In addition to serial digital data exchange, the USB standard also provides 5 VDC power, up to 500 mA (900 mA over USB 3.0).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Numerous accessory gadgets ("USB decorations") were designed to connect to USB only for DC power and not for data interchange.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] The USB Implementers Forum in March, 2007 released the USB Battery Charging Specification which defines, "...limits as well as detection, control and reporting mechanisms to permit devices to draw current in excess of the USB 2.0 specification for charging ...".
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Electric fans, lamps, alarms, coffee warmers, battery chargers, and even toys have been designed to tap power from a USB connector.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Plug-in adapters equipped with USB receptacles are widely available to convert 120 VAC or 240 VAC power or 12 VDC automotive power to 5 VDC USB power (see photo at right).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] The trend towards more-compact electronic devices has driven a shift towards the micro-USB and mini-USB connectors, which are electrically compatible in function to the original USB connector but physically smaller.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] In 2012, a USB Power Delivery Specification was proposed to standardize delivery of up to 100 watts (increased to 240 W in 2021), suitable for devices such as laptop computers that usually depend on proprietary adapters.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] The ITU published Recommendation ITU-T L.1000, "Universal power adapter and charger solution for mobile terminals and other hand-held ICT devices", which specifies a charger similar in most respects to that of the GSMA/OMTP proposal and to the European Common external power supply.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] The ITU recommendation was expanded and updated in June, 2011.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] The hope is to markedly reduce the profusion of non-interchangeable power adapters.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] The European Union defined a Common external power supply for "hand-held data-enabled mobile phones" (smartphones) sold from 2010, intended to replace the many incompatible proprietary power supplies and eliminate waste by reducing the total number of supplies manufactured.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] Conformant supplies deliver 5 VDC via a micro-USB connector, with preferred input voltage handled ranging from 90 to 264 VAC.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] In 2006 Larry Page, a founder of Google, proposed a 12 V and up to 15 A standard for almost all equipment requiring an external converter, with new buildings fitted with 12 VDC wiring, making external AC-to-DC adapter circuitry unnecessary.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-adapter] IEC has created a standard for interchangeable laptop power supplies, IEC 62700 (full name "IEC Technical Specification 62700: DC Power supply for notebook computer"), which was published on February 6, 2014.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and sockets may sometimes combine male and female contacts.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and wall-mounted sockets for portable appliances became available in the 1880s, to replace connections to light sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A proliferation of types were subsequently developed for both convenience and protection from electrical injury.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Electrical plugs and sockets differ from one another in voltage and current rating, shape, size, and connector type.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Different standard systems of plugs and sockets are used around the world, and many obsolete socket types are still found in older buildings.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Coordination of technical standards has allowed some types of plug to be used across large regions to facilitate the production and import of electrical appliances and for the convenience of travellers.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some multi-standard sockets allow use of several types of plug.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Incompatible sockets and plugs may be used with the help of adaptors, though these may not always provide full safety and performance.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Single-phase sockets have receptacles for two power pins, one to carry the electrical current from the power source to the connected device (called *live*, *line*, or *phase pin*) and another one to carry it back to the power source (called *neutral pin*).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many sockets have a third receptacle or pin for a safety connection to earth ground.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is a *male* connector, usually with protruding pins that match the receptacles (*female* contacts) in a socket.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs also have a female contact, used only for the earth ground connection.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Typically no energy is supplied to any exposed pins or terminals on the socket, hence the power pins are always part of the plug rather than the socket.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In addition to the recessed contacts of the energised socket, plug and socket systems often have other safety features to reduce the risk of electric shock or damage to appliances.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] When commercial electric power was first introduced in the 1880s, it was used primarily for lighting.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Other portable appliances (such as vacuum cleaners, electric fans, smoothing irons, and curling-tong heaters) were connected to light-bulb sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] As early as 1885 a two-pin plug and wall socket format was available on the British market.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] By about 1910 the first three-pin earthed (grounded) plugs appeared.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Over time other safety improvements were gradually introduced to the market.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] One of the first national standards for plugs and wall sockets was enacted in 1915 in the UK.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Designs of plugs and sockets have gradually developed to reduce the risk of electric shock and fire.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs are shaped to prevent bodily contact with live parts.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may be recessed and plugs designed to fit closely within the recess to reduce risk of a user contacting the live pins.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Contact pins may be sheathed with insulation over part of their length, so as to reduce exposure of energized metal during insertion or removal of the plug.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may have automatic shutters to stop foreign objects from being inserted into energized contacts.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets are often set into a surround which prevents accidental contact with the live wires in the wall behind it.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some also have an integrated cover (e.g. a hinged flap) covering the socket itself when not in use, or a switch to turn off the socket.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs, particularly the British Type G, have a built-in fuse which breaks the circuit if too much current flows.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A third contact for a connection to earth is intended to protect against insulation failure of the connected device.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some early unearthed plug and socket types were revised to include an earthing pin or phased out in favour of earthed types.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is often designed so that the earth ground contact connects before the energized circuit contacts.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The assigned IEC appliance class is governed by the requirement for earthing or equivalent protection.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Class I equipment requires an earth contact in the plug and socket, while Class II equipment is unearthed and protects the user with double insulation.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Where a "neutral" conductor exists in supply wiring, polarization of the plug can improve safety by preserving the distinction in the equipment.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, appliances may ensure that switches interrupt the live side of the circuit, or can connect the shell of a screw-base lampholder to neutral to reduce electric shock hazard.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some designs, polarized plugs cannot be mated with non-polarized sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In most NEMA 1 plugs, for example, the neutral blade is slightly wider than the hot blade, so it can only be inserted one way.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Wiring systems where both circuit conductors have a significant potential with respect to earth do not benefit from polarized plugs.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and power cords have a rated voltage and current assigned to them by the manufacturer.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Using a plug or power cord that is inappropriate for the load may be a safety hazard.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, high-current equipment can cause a fire when plugged into an extension cord with a current rating lower than necessary.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sometimes the cords used to plug in dual voltage 120 V / 240 V equipment are rated only for 125 V, so care must be taken by travellers to use only cords with an appropriate voltage rating.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Various methods can be used to increase the number or reach of sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Extension cords (extension leads) are used for temporary connections when a socket is not within convenient reach of an appliance's power lead.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This may be in the form of a single socket on a flexible cable or a power strip with multiple sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A power strip may also have switches, surge voltage protection, or overcurrent protection.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Multisocket adaptors (or "splitters") allow the connection of two or more plugs to a single socket.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are manufactured in various configurations, depending on the country and the region in which they are used, with various ratings.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This allows connecting more than one electrical consumer item to one single socket and is mainly used for low power devices (TV sets, table lamps, computers, etc.).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are usually rated for 6 A, 10 A, or 16 A at 250 V or for 15 A or less at 125 V.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some countries such adaptors are banned and are not available in shops, as they may lead to fires due to overloading them or can cause excessive mechanical stress to wall-mounted sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors can be made with ceramic, Bakelite, or other plastic bodies.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] but is intended to accept a number of different plug types.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Old Chinese dual socket accepting both unearthed two-pin (upper) and earthed three-pin (lower) plugs.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] "Hybrid", "multi-standard", or "universal" sockets are intended to accommodate plugs of two or more types.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some jurisdictions, they violate safety standards for sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Safety advocates, the United States Army, and a manufacturer of sockets point out a number of safety issues with universal socket and adaptors, including voltage mismatch, exposure of live pins, lack of proper earth ground connection, or lack of protection from overload or short circuit.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Universal sockets may not meet technical standards for durability, plug retention force, temperature rise of components, or other performance requirements, as they are outside the scope of national and international technical standards.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A technical standard may include compatibility of a socket with more than one form of plug.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The Thai dual socket is specified in figure 4 of TIS 166-2549 and is designed to accept Thai plugs, and also Type A, B, and C plugs.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Chinese dual sockets have both an unearthed socket that accepts A and C plugs and an earthed socket that accepts Type I plugs.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Since the 2021 revision of the Chinese standard, the installation of such dual sockets is no longer allowed in China, but they can still be found in many existing installations.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Such Thai or Chinese dual sockets also accept plugs normally fitted to 120 V appliances (e.g.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] 120 V rated NEMA 1-15 ungrounded plugs).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This can cause an electrical incompatibility, since both countries supply residential power at 220–230 V.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] These dual sockets also accept French and Schuko plugs (Types E and F), but unsafely: no earth contact is established and live pins may be exposed when a plug is partially inserted.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Commonly, manufacturers provide an IEC 60320 inlet on an appliance, with a detachable power cord (mains flex lead) and appropriate plug in order to avoid manufacturing whole appliances, with the only difference being the type of plug.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Alternatively, the plug itself can often be swappable using standard or proprietary connectors.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors between standards are not included in most standards, and as a result they have no formal quality criteria defined.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Physical compatibility does not ensure that the appliance and socket match in frequency or voltage.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors allow travellers to connect devices to foreign sockets, but do not change voltage or frequency.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A voltage converter is required for electrical compatibility in places with a different voltage than the device is designed for.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Mismatch in frequency between supply and appliances may still cause problems even at the correct voltage.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some appliances have a switch for the selection of voltage.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many modern devices use AC adapters that accept 100–240 V voltage at 50 or 60 Hz, meaning they can be used anywhere in the world as long as a suitable plug adapter is used.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used in a given area are regulated by local governments.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) maintains a guide with letter designations for generally compatible types of plugs, which expands on earlier guides published by the United States Department of Commerce.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a *de facto* naming standard and guide to travellers.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some letter types correspond to several current ratings or different technical standards, so the letter does not uniquely identify a plug and socket within the type family, nor guarantee compatibility.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physical compatibility of the plug and socket does not ensure correct voltage, frequency, or current capacity.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Not all plug and socket families have letters in the IEC guide, but those that have are noted in this article, as are some additional letters commonly used by retail vendors.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Europe, CENELEC publishes a list of approved plug and socket technical standards used in the member countries.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A number of countries in Oceania as well as China and Argentina use a plug that has two flat pins at an angle, forming a V-shape, as well as a flat vertical grounding pin.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the exact pin dimensions and the polarity vary between different countries, these plugs and sockets are all compatible with each other and are known as *Type I*.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system used in Argentina is defined by several standards of the Argentine Normalization and Certification Institute (IRAM).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2071 defines two sockets that have the same form factor, but differ in size and rating.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The smaller, more common socket is rated for 10 A.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The larger variant, rated for 20 A, is mostly used for higher-power appliances such as air conditioners.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2073 defines the corresponding plugs used for Class I appliances (that require earthing).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system has an earthing pin and two flat current-carrying pins forming an inverted V-shape (120°).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The power pins are set at 30° to the vertical with a distance of 7.92 mm (0.312 in) from their centres to the centre of the plug; they are 18.2 mm (0.717 in) long.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is 21.4 mm (0.843 in) long and placed below the plug centre at a distance of 10.31 mm (0.406 in).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 20 A version are larger – 8.0 by 1.9 mm (0.315 by 0.075 in) – and placed further away from the centre of the plug – 9.53 mm (0.375 in) for the power pins, 11.1 mm (0.437 in) for the earthing pin.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] At 21.8 mm (0.858 in), the earthing pin is a bit longer, while the power pins are a bit shorter at 17.8 mm (0.701 in).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is also an unearthed version of the 10 A plug, defined by IRAM 2063, that lacks an earthing pin and can be used with Class II appliances.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs, on the other hand, must always provide earthing.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Insulating sleeves around the upper parts of the power pins are allowed, but not required.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used, they significantly reduce the risk of electric shock from accidentally touching the pins of a partially inserted plug.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the pins of the 20 A plug are placed farther apart than those of the 10 A plug, the two Argentine plug types are mutually incompatible.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is not possible to insert a 20 A plug into a 10 A socket or vice versa.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The most important difference from the Australasian and Chinese plugs is that the Argentine plug is wired with the live and neutral contacts reversed.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Argentina, when the earth contact is positioned downward, the live (line) contact is on the right side of the socket, while in Australasia and China it is on the left (assuming the same orientation).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Brazil, Type I–style plugs and sockets are still commonly used in old installations for high-power appliances like air conditioners, dishwashers, and household ovens.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are often called "Argentine plugs" and are indeed physically identical to the IRAM plugs rated for 20 A, though they might have been developed independently on the basis of the American NEMA 10-20 standard (which uses the same form factor).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While these plugs are sometimes used for normal single-phase power and wired in the same way as in Argentina, some are wired for split-phase power with two "hot" (or phase) wires and a neutral wire, but no earth connection.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Care must therefore be taken that the same wiring scheme is used in the socket and in the plug, since otherwise the equipment would surely be damaged.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In newer installations, the 20 A version of the Type N plug, adopted by Brazil as national standard NBR 14136, is generally preferred.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Australian/New Zealand standard is used in Australia, New Zealand, Fiji, Tonga, Solomon Islands, and Papua New Guinea.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug shape and basic dimensions are identical to the 10 A plug used in Argentina.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Australasian standard defines a series of plugs and sockets for devices drawing up to 10, 15, 20, 25 and 32 A that are one-way compatible.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] All sockets accept plugs of equal or lower current ratings, but not higher.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, a 10 A plug will fit all sockets but a 20 A plug will fit only 20, 25 and 32 A sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The three flat pins all measure 6.35 by 1.63 mm (0.250 by 0.064 in) – very slightly larger than in Argentina.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The length of the power pins is 17.06 mm (0.672 in), while the earthing pin has a length of 19.94 mm (0.785 in) – somewhat shorter than in Argentina.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 15 A plug, the height of the earth pin is increased from 6.35 to 9.08 mm (0.357 in), while the dimensions of the power pins remain the same.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 20 A plug, however, their height is increased in the same way, so that the surface dimensions of the three pins are again identical.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 25 A version, the earthing pin takes the shape of an inverted L (an extra bar is added at the top end), and in the 32 A version it takes the shape of a sideways U (extra bars are added at both ends).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In general, only 10 A and 15 A socket outlets are likely to be encountered in domestic or commercial installations.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A sockets are rare and higher rated ones are very rare.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An unearthed version of the 10 A plug with two angled power pins but no earthing pin is used with double-insulated appliances, but sockets and higher-rated plugs always include an earth contact.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In New Zealand, PDL 940 "tap-on" or "piggy-back" plugs are available which allow a second 10 A plug to be fitted to the rear of the plug.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Australia these piggy-back plugs are now available only on pre-made extension leads.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A novel feature of modern Australian socket outlets is a snap-fitting surround for the socket, covering the screws that affix the socket to the wall, and extending all the way around the socket periphery.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Australia's standard plug/socket system was originally codified as standard C112 (floated provisionally in 1937, and adopted as a formal standard in 1938), which was based on a design patented by Harvey Hubbell and was superseded by AS 3112 in 1990.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The requirement for insulated pins was introduced in the 2000 revision, and became effective 5 years after its publication.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard for Mainland Chinese plugs and sockets (excluding Hong Kong and Macau) is set out in GB 2099.1 and GB 1002.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] As part of China's commitment for entry into the WTO, the new CPCS (Compulsory Product Certification System) has been introduced, and compliant Chinese plugs have been awarded the CCC Mark by this system.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs are three-wire, earthed, rated for 10 or 16 A, 250 V, and are chiefly used for Class I applications.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 10 A version are 1.55 mm (0.061 in) thick by 6.4 mm (0.252 in) wide; the centres of the power pins are placed 7.9 mm (0.311 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 10.3 mm (0.406 in) away.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In both plug types, the live and neutral pins are 18 mm (0.709 in) long, while the earth pin is 21 mm (0.827 in) long.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes the 10 A version compatible with Argentine and Australasian 10 A sockets, as their dimensions are nearly identical.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except for the pin length, all dimensions of the 16 A version are slightly larger.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Its pins are 1.8 by 8.1 mm (0.071 by 0.319 in); the centres of the power pins are placed 9.5 mm (0.374 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 11.1 mm (0.437 in) away.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes this plug compatible with the 20 A sockets used in Argentina.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is, however, incompatible with Chinese 10 A sockets as well as all Australasian sockets because of the different pin spacing.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some sockets in China include a physical lockout preventing access to the active and neutral terminals unless an earth pin (which is slightly longer than the other two pins) is entered first; others require pins to be inserted into both live terminals to open the shutter.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since its 2024 revision, GB 1002 also defines unearthed two-pin Class II plugs, though such plugs cannot be inserted into sockets that require an earth pin to open the shutters.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Already since 2008 for 16 A, and since 2021 also for 10 A, there is an unearthed Class II plug variant that uses an unwired dummy earth pin to open the shutters; unearthed plugs of this kind fit into all Chinese sockets of the same rating.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] China also uses American/Japanese NEMA 1-15 sockets and plugs for Class II appliances (however, polarized plugs with one prong wider than the other are not accepted).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older versions of GB 1002 also defined a socket type that accepts Europlugs (Type C), but this hybrid socket was removed from the 2021 revision of the standard.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The voltage at a Chinese socket of any type is 220 V.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In China, sockets typically have the earth contact above the power pins, while in Argentina and Australasia it is usually positioned below them.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While Australasian plugs have insulating sleeves around the upper part of their power pins, that is not the case for most existing Chinese plugs, hence their pins may become live while there is still a large enough gap between the faces of the plug and socket to allow a finger to touch the pin.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2022, insulating sleeves are also allowed on plugs sold in China; they will be mandatory from 2027.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The polarity of all grounded British sockets is standardized: earth is at the top and live is at the right of the socket.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This convention is also followed in other countries using these plugs and sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 546, "Two-pole and earthing-pin plugs, socket-outlets and socket-outlet adaptors for AC (50-60 Hz) circuits up to 250 V" describes four sizes of plug rated at 2 A, 5 A (Type D), 15 A (Type M) and 30 A.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs have three round pins arranged in a triangle, with the larger top pin being the earthing pin.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plugs are non-interchangeable between current ratings.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Introduced in 1934, the BS 546 type has mostly been displaced in the UK by the BS 1363 standard.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC, some 40 countries use Type D (among them India) and about 15 countries use Type M.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 1363 "13 A plugs, socket-outlets, adaptors and connection units" is the main plug and socket type used in the United Kingdom.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC it is also used in over 50 countries worldwide.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some of these countries have national standards based on BS 1363, including Bahrain, Hong Kong, Ireland, Cyprus, Macau, Malaysia, Malta, Saudi Arabia, Singapore, Brunei, Sri Lanka, and the UAE.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug has three rectangular pins forming an isosceles triangle.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The BS 1363 plug has a fuse rated to protect its flexible cord from overload and consequent fire risk.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern appliances may only be sold with a fuse of the appropriate size pre-installed.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The United Kingdom, Ireland, and Malta use the BS 4573 two-pin plug and socket for electric shavers and toothbrushes.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has insulating sleeves on the pins.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Although similar to the Europlug Type C, the diameter and spacing of the pins are slightly different and hence it will not fit into a Schuko socket.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are, however, two-pin sockets and adaptors which will accept both BS 4573 and Europlugs.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The **CEE 7** standard is a set of general specifications and standard sheets for AC plugs and sockets, first created by the IECEE standards body in 1951.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They are now the main system in use in most of Europe.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 incorporates the two round pinned (with centres spaced at 19 mm) Schuko or Type F plug that was patented by Siemens-Schuckertwerke in 1929, and also the Type E plug, likely developed in Belgium around 1930 but never patented, therefore adopted by Czecho­slovakia, Poland and France.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 have also developed and incorporated "universal" plugs that will work on both Type E and Type F sockets such as the Europlug.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] European countries (whether EU or non-EU) each have their own regulations and national standards; for example, some require child-resistant shutters, while others do not.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CE marking is neither applicable nor permitted on plugs and sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7 system has been adapted in many countries outside of Europe as well.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 sockets and CEE 7/2 plugs are 2-pole connectors rated 10/16 A up to 250 V, with 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in) pins.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It has no protective earth and therefore poses a risk of electric shock due to missing circular recess.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Their sale or use has been banned in a number of countries.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/3 socket and CEE 7/4 plug are commonly called *Schuko*, an abbreviation for *Schutzkontakt*, *Protective contact* to earth ("Schuko" itself is a registered trademark of a German association established to own the term).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes and two earthing clips that engage before live pin contact is made.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Schuko system is unpolarized, allowing live and neutral to be reversed.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is used in most European countries and on other continents, including in South Korea and Uruguay.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The European countries not using it at all are Belgium, Czech Republic, Cyprus, Ireland, Liechtenstein, Malta, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom; those not using it predominantly are Denmark, Faroe Islands, France, Italy, Monaco, San Marino, and Slovakia.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This electrical connector most likely originated in Belgium, where it was introduced in the 1930s by Vynckier Frères as well as Niko.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket and CEE 7/6 plug are defined in several national standards, among them the Belgian NBN C 61‑112, the French NF C 61-314, and the Czech ČSN 35 4516.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket is in Europe the primary standard of Belgium, Czechia, France, Poland, and Slovakia.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Denmark including the Faroe Islands and Greenland, both CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 are nowadays explicitly allowed alongside Type K.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The round earth pin projecting from the socket connects before the energized contacts touch.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin is centred between the apertures, offset by 10 mm (0.394 in).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in), spaced 19 mm (0.748 in) apart and with an aperture for the socket's projecting earth pin.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 plugs have been designed to solve this incompatibility by being able to fit in either type of socket.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is rated at 16 A and looks similar to CEE 7/4 plugs, but with earth contacts to fit both CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/3 sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to its compatibility with the inherently unpolarized Schuko (CEE 7/4) plugs, appliances using it cannot expect the current to flow in any particular direction.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/16 Alternative I unearthed plug is used for unearthed appliances.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative I is a round plug with cutouts to make it compatible with CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (The similar-appearing CEE 7/17 has larger pins and a higher current rating.) This alternative is seldom used.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative II, popularly known as the Europlug, is a flat 2.5 A-rated plug with two round 4 by 19 mm (0.157 by 0.748 in) pins, defined by Cenelec standard EN 50075 and national equivalents.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is not rewirable and must be supplied with a flexible cord.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It can be inserted in either direction, so live and neutral are connected arbitrarily.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] To improve contact with socket parts the Europlug has slightly flexible pins which converge toward their free ends.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is widely used in most of Europe and parts of the Middle East, Africa, South America, and Asia.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is no socket defined to accept only the Europlug.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Instead, it fits a range of sockets including all three CEE 7 sockets (unearthed, German/"Schuko", and Belgian/French) and also many non-CEE 7 standard sockets such as Swiss, Danish and Italian (10 A) ones as well as Israeli sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] British shaver sockets also accept Europlugs, although in this configuration the connection supply is only rated at 200 mA.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a round plug compatible with all three types of CEE 7 sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also called the "contour plug", it has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins are not sheathed, in contrast to e.g.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Danish standard plug is described in the Danish Plug Equipment Section 107-2-D1 Standard sheet (SRAF1962/DB 16/87 DN10A-R).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Like in most European plugs, the power pins of Danish plugs are 19 mm (0.75 in) long and spaced 19 mm (0.75 in) apart, with a diameter of 4.8 mm (0.19 in).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is part of the plug (in contrast to French and Schuko plugs); it is D-shaped, 14 mm (0.55 in) long, and offset from the power pins by 13 mm (0.51 in).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is 4 mm (0.16 in) thick with a diameter of 6.5 mm (0.26 in).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Danish standard provides for sockets to have child-resistant shutters.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized in the same way as British ones: if earth is at the bottom, live is at the left of the socket.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Europlugs (CEE 7/16) and contour plugs (CEE 7/17) can safely be used with Danish sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physically the sockets also accept earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko), CEE 7/6 (French), and CEE 7/7 (Schuko-French hybrid) plugs, but no earth connection will be established.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore news sites and industry magazines warn that plugging these directly into a Type K socket can give noticeable electric shocks, be dangerous and even be life-threatening.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Traditionally all Danish sockets were equipped with a switch to prevent touching live pins when connecting/disconnecting the plug.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Today, sockets without switch are allowed, but they must be recessed to prevent touching the live pins.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since the early 1990s earthed sockets have been required in all new electric installations in Denmark.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets need not be earthed, but all sockets, including old installations, must be protected by earth-fault interrupters by 1 July 2008.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A variation (standard DK 2-5a) of the Danish plug is for use only on surge protected computer sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It fits into the corresponding computer socket and the normal socket, but normal plugs deliberately do not fit into the special computer socket.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is often used in companies, but rarely in private homes.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is another variation for hospital equipment with a rectangular left pin, which is used for life support equipment.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1986, the International Electrotechnical Commission published IEC 60906-1, a specification for a plug and socket that look similar, but are not identical, to the Swiss plug and socket.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This standard was intended to one day become common for all of Europe and other regions with 230 V mains, but the effort to adopt it as a European Union standard was put on hold in the mid-1990s.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket are rated 16 A 250 V AC and are intended for use only on systems having nominal voltages between 200 V and 250 V AC.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug pins are 4.5 mm in diameter, live and neutral are on centres 19 mm apart.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The live pin is on the right when looking at a socket with the earth pin offset up.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shutters over the live and neutral pins are mandatory.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The first country to have officially adopted the standard is South Africa (as SANS 164-2).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Paraguay has also adopted it as national standard (PNA-IEC 60906-1), but so far its application is voluntary, and as of March 2025, there is no indication that sockets of this type are commonly installed in the country.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil developed a plug resembling IEC 60906-1 as the national standard under specification NBR 14136.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NBR 14136 standard has two versions, neither of which has pin dimensions or ratings complying with IEC 60906-1.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Use at 127 V is permitted by NBR 14136, which is against the intention of IEC 60906-1.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] South Africa adopted IEC 60906-1 as its national standard, SANS 164-2, in 1992.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard specifies both a 2-pin unearthed and 3-pin earthed plug system, equivalent to IEC Type N.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SANS 164-2 was designated the "preferred standard" in 2013, and South Africa is in the process of transitioning to it as the dominant system, expected to be completed by 2025 to 2035.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The SANS 164-2 system is compatible with the SANS 164-5 Europlug, commonly used in the country.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This transition aims to improve electrical safety and standardization, aligning South Africa with international plug and socket systems.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil, which had been using mostly Europlugs as well as NEMA 1-15 and NEMA 5-15 plugs, adopted a (non-compliant) variant of IEC 60906-1 as the national standard in 1998 under specification NBR 14136 (revised in 2002).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are used for both 220-volt and 127-volt regions of the country, despite the IEC 60906-2 recommendation that NEMA 5-15 be used for 120 V connections.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two types of sockets and plugs in NBR 14136: one for 10 A, with a 4.0 mm pin diameter, and another for 20 A, with a 4.8 mm pin diameter.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This differs from IEC 60906-1 which specifies a pin diameter of 4.5 mm and a rating of 16 A.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 does not require shutters on the apertures, a further aspect of non-compliance with IEC 60906-1.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 was not enforced in that country until 2007, when its adoption was made optional for manufacturers.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Few private houses in Brazil have an earthed supply, so even if a three-pin socket is present it is not safe to assume that all three terminals are actually connected.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most large domestic appliances were sold with the option to fit a flying earth tail to be locally earthed, but many consumers were unsure how to use this and so did not connect it.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The new standard has an earth pin, which in theory eliminates the need for the flying earth tail.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to their smaller pin diameter, Brazilian plugs rated for 10 A also fit into Brazilian sockets rated for 20 A and South African sockets rated for 16 A.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs do not fit into 10 A sockets, which is as intended.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, if the Brazilian and South African variants are mixed, due to receptacle tolerances it might be possible to insert a 16 A plug into a 10 A socket or a 20 A plug into a 16 A socket, which could overload the socket.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug defined in SI 32 (IS16A-R) is used only in Israel, the Gaza Strip and the West Bank.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two versions: an older one with flat pins, and a newer one with round pins.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pre-1989 system has three flat pins in a Y-shape, with live and neutral 19 mm (0.75 in) apart.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Pre-1989 sockets which accept only old-style plugs have become very rare in Israel.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets have a defined polarity; looking at the front, neutral is to the left, ground at the bottom, and live to the right.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Italian plugs and sockets are defined by the standard CEI 23-50 and referred to as "Type L".
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This includes models rated at 10 A and 16 A that differ in contact diameter and spacing.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both are symmetrical, allowing the live and neutral contacts to be inserted in either direction.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The 10 A plug has 4 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 19 mm apart, while the 16 A plug has 5 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 26 mm apart.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug type is also used in Chile and Uruguay.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern installations in Italy (and in other countries where Type L plugs are used) typically use sockets that accept several plug types.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The simplest type, designated CEI 23-50 P17/11, has a central round hole flanked by two figure-8 shaped holes, allowing the insertion of Italian 10 A and 16 A plugs as well as Europlugs.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These compact hybrid sockets are known as *presa bipasso* (twin-gauge socket).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A larger, but more flexible hybrid socket is called CEI 23-50 P40.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It merges the *bipasso* form factor with a "Schuko" socket, thus also accepting earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko) and CEE 7/7 (CEE hybrid) as well as unearthed CEE 7/17 ("contour") plugs.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Many appliances sold in Italy today are equipped with hybrid CEE 7/7 or CEE 7/17 plugs, but only these larger CEI 23-50 P40 sockets will accept them without an adapter.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, adaptors that allow plugging them into smaller sockets are also commonly sold and regulated by a specific standard.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ordinary duplex socket mounted in ground-pin down orientation.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most of North America and Central America, and some of South America, use connectors standardized by the National Electrical Manufacturers Association (NEMA).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The devices are named using the format NEMA n-mmX, where *n* is an identifier for the configuration of pins and blades, *mm* is the maximum current rating, and *X* is either P for plug or R for receptacle.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, NEMA 5-15R is a configuration type 5 receptacle supporting 15 A.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Corresponding *P* and *R* versions are designed to be mated.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Within the series, the arrangement and size of pins will differ, to prevent accidental mating of devices with a higher current draw than the receptacle can support.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA-1 plugs have two parallel blades and are rated 15 A at 125 volts.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They provide no ground connection but will fit into a grounding NEMA 5-15 receptacle.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Early versions were not polarized, but today most plugs are polarized via a wider neutral blade.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (Unpolarized AC adaptors are a common exception.) Harvey Hubbell patented a parallel blade plug in 1913, where the blades were equal width (U.S. patent 1,064,833).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1916 Hubbell received a patent for a polarized version where one blade was both longer and wider than the other (U.S. patent 1,180,648).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the polarized version of NEMA 1-15, introduced in the 1950s, both blades are the same length, with only the width varying.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ungrounded NEMA-1 outlets are not permitted in new construction in the United States and Canada, but can still be found in older buildings.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-15 plug has two flat parallel blades like NEMA 1-15, and a ground (earth) pin.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground pin is longer than the live and neutral blades, such that an inserted plug connects to ground before power.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground hole is officially D-shaped, although some round holes exist and many plugs have round ground pins.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both current-carrying blades on grounding plugs may be narrow, since the ground pin enforces polarity, but outlets have a wider opening for the neutral blade to prevent ungrounded polarized plugs from being put in backwards.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This socket is recommended in IEC standard 60906-2 for 120-volt 60 Hz installations.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The National Electrical Contractors Association's installation standard (NEIS 130-2016) requires a consistent orientation for sockets installed together or nearby, but does not prescribe any specific orientation.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In practice, most sockets are mounted with the ground contact below the other contacts.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This ground-down orientation has been called the "sad socket", "dismayed face", or "shocked face" – names which reflect pareidolia.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Tamper-resistant sockets may be required in new residential construction, with shutters on the power blade sockets to prevent contact by objects inserted into the socket.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In stage lighting, this connector is sometimes known as *PBG* for *Parallel Blade with Ground*, *Edison* or *Hubbell*, the name of a common manufacturer.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-20 AP variant has blades perpendicular to each other.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The receptacle has a T-slot for the neutral blade which accepts either 15 A parallel-blade plugs or 20 A plugs.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA 14-50 devices are frequently found in RV parks, since they are used for "shore power" connections of larger recreational vehicles.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also, it was formerly common to connect mobile homes to utility power via a 14-50 device.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Newer applications include Tesla's Mobile Connector for vehicle charging, which formally recommended the installation of a 14-50 receptacle for home use.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 240 V 20-, 30- and 50-amp rated sockets are often used for high-current appliances such as air conditioners, clothes dryers and electric stoves, respectively.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Japanese Class II plug and socket appear physically identical to NEMA 1-15 and also carries 15 A.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The relevant Japanese Industrial Standards, JIS C 8303, imposes stricter dimensional requirements for the plug housing, different marking requirements, and mandatory testing and type approval.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older Japanese sockets and multi-plug adaptors are unpolarized—the slots in the sockets are the same size—and will accept only unpolarized plugs.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japanese plugs generally fit into most North American sockets without modification, but polarized North American plugs may require adaptors or replacement non-polarized plugs to connect to older Japanese sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Japan the voltage is 100 V, and the frequency is either 50 Hz (Eastern Japan: Tokyo, Yokohama, Tohoku, Kawasaki, Sapporo, Sendai and Hokkaido) or 60 Hz (Western Japan: Osaka, Kyoto, Nagoya, Shikoku, Kyushu and Hiroshima) depending on whether the customer is located on the Osaka or Tokyo grid.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore, some North American devices which can be physically plugged into Japanese sockets may not function properly.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japan also uses a grounded plug similar to the North American NEMA 5-15.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, it is less common than its NEMA 1-15 equivalent.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2005, new Japanese homes are required to have class I grounded sockets for connecting domestic appliances.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This rule does not apply for sockets not intended to be used for domestic appliances, but it is strongly advised to have class I sockets throughout the home.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Swiss standard, also used in Liechtenstein, is *SN 441011* (*SN SEV 1011 until 2019) Plugs and socket-outlets for household and similar purposes*.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard defines a hierarchical system of plugs and sockets with two, three and five pins, and 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets will accept plugs with the same or fewer pins and the same or lower ratings.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard does not require the use of child protective shutters.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 defines a "Type 1x" series of 10 A plugs and sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 11 plug is unearthed, with two 4 mm diameter round pins spaced 19 mm apart.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 12 plug adds a central 4 mm diameter round earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The obsolete type 12 socket had no recess, while the newer type 13 socket is recessed.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both sockets will accept type 11 and type 12 plugs, and also the 2.5 A Europlug.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Earlier type 11 and 12 plugs had live and neutral pins without sleeved pins, which present a shock hazard when partially inserted into non-recessed sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The IEC Type J designation refers to SEV 1011's type 12 plugs and type 13 sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unique to Switzerland is a three-phase power socket compatible with single-phase plugs: The type 15 plug has three round pins, of the same dimensions as type 12, plus two smaller flat rectangular pins for two additional power phases.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 15 socket is recessed, and has five openings (three round and two flat rectangular).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 15 and the Europlug.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 also defines a "Type 2x" series of 16 A plugs and sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are the same as their 10 A "Type 1x" counterparts, but replace the round pins with 4 mm × 5 mm rectangular pins.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The sockets will also accept "Type 1x" plugs.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The unearthed type 21 plug has two rectangular pins, with centres 19 mm apart.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 23 plug adds a central rectangular earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recessed type 23 socket will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 21, 23 and the Europlug.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Again, the three-phase power socket is compatible with single-phase plugs, either of 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 25 plug has three rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 23, plus two rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 15.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding type 25 socket is recessed and will accept all Swiss plug types as well as the Europlug.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Thai Industrial Standard (TIS) 166-2547 and its subsequent update TIS 166-2549 replaced prior standards which were based on NEMA 1-15 and 5-15, as Thailand uses 230 V electricity.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round power pins 4.8 mm in diameter and 19 mm in length, insulated for 10 mm and spaced 19 mm apart, with an earthing pin of the same diameter and 21.4 mm in length, located 11.89 mm from the line connecting the two power pins.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin spacing corresponds to that of NEMA 5 and provides compatibility with prior hybrid three-pin sockets, which accept NEMA 1-15, NEMA 5-15, and Europlugs, all of which have been variably used in Thailand.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard also defines an ungrounded plug with a smaller form factor that is very similar to the Europlug (but a bit higher); its power pins are identical to the grounded variant and both are rated for up to 16 A (while the Europlug is only rated for 2.5 A).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The generally used hybrid socket is also defined in TIS 166-2547, in addition to a plain three-round-pin socket, with plans to eventually replace the former and phase out support for NEMA-compatible plugs.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized (as in NEMA 5-15).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The grounded plug is similar to, but not interchangeable with, the Israeli SI32 plug.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Thai plug is designated as "Type O" at IEC World Plugs.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special purpose sockets may be found in residential, industrial, commercial or institutional buildings.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special-purpose sockets may be labelled or coloured to identify a reserved use of a system, or may have keys or specially shaped pins to prevent use of unintended equipment.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used to power electric stoves from a single-phase line have to be rated for greater current values than those used with three-phase supply because all the power has to be transferred through two contacts, not three.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] If not hardwired to the supply, electric stoves may be connected to the mains with an appropriate high power connector.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some countries do not have wiring regulations for single-phase electric stoves.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Russia, an electric stove can often be seen connected with a 25, 32, or even 40 A connector.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Norway, a 25 A grounded connector, rectangular shaped with rounded corners, is used for single-phase stoves.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The connector has three rectangular pins in a row, with the grounding pin longer than other two.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding socket is recessed to prevent shocks.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Norwegian standard is NEK 502:2005 – standard sheet X (socket) and sheet XI (plug).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] National wiring regulations sometimes prohibit the use of sockets adjacent to water taps, etc.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A special socket, with an isolation transformer, may allow electric razors to be used near a sink.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the isolation transformer is of low rating, such outlets are not suitable to operate higher-powered appliances such as hair dryers.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An IEC standard 61558-2-5, adopted by CENELEC and as a national standard in some countries, describes one type of shaver supply unit.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver sockets may accept multiple two-pin plug types including Australian (Type I) and BS 4573.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The isolation transformer often includes a 115 V output accepting two-pin US plugs (Type A).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver supply units must also be current limited, IEC 61558-2-5 specifies a minimum rating of 20 VA and maximum of 50 VA.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are marked with a shaver symbol, and may also say "shavers only".
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Isolation transformers and dedicated NEMA 1-15 shaver receptacles were once standard installation practice in North America, but now a GFCI receptacle is used instead.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This provides the full capacity of a standard receptacle but protects the user of a razor or other appliance from leakage current.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Though BS 4573 plugs look similar to Europlugs (Type C), there are subtle differences between them.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the BS 4573 plug has round 5 mm contacts, spaced at 16 mm, the Europlug has 4 mm contacts, spaced at (roughly) 19 mm.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In order to insert a Europlug into a BS 4573 socket, an adaptor should be used.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Polarized plugs have a wider neutral blade; sockets accept both polarized and unpolarized plugs.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/17 specifies an unearthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are some CEE 7/17 plugs with special shape which are polarized when used with CEE 7/5 sockets (mechanically only).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6, CEE 7/7, and CEE 7/17 plugs.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used in CEE 7/1 (unearthed) sockets or "universal adaptors" there is no protection for those plugs.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 socket accepts earthed CEE 7/3, CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/7 plugs but provides no earth connection.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets can have a very shallow recess.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 4573 and BS EN 61558-2-5 do not explicitly specify a current rating for a compliant plug, see BS 4573 section of British and compatible standards.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 specifies an earthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plug can only be inserted one way with French CEE 7/5, but lack of wiring convention means that the system is not polarized.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The actual rating of non-rewirable plugs is marked according to the fuse fitted by the cord set manufacturer, the fuse rating being determined by the rating of the flexible cable.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also accepts unearthed Class II plugs that include an unwired dummy earth pin.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except when used with unearthed plugs such as the Europlug.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets may be recessed by 8.3 mm, but few are.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are unearthed Class II plugs with an unwired dummy earth pin, accepted by all sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are also unearthed Class II plugs without an earth pin, accepted only by sockets that do not have an earth-pin-driven shutter.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Import of plugs with non-partially-insulated pins no longer allowed after 2012.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unrecessed type 12 sockets may no longer be installed since 2017.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by some Danish sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of plugs.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets must be recessed or equipped with a switch that allows them to be turned off.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Type L comes in two variations with ratings of 10 A and 16 A having different pin diameters and spacing from each other.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also used in Paraguay (PNA-IEC 60906-1).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Italian bypass lampholder plugs with Edison screw mount.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] A lampholder plug fits into a light socket in place of a light bulb to connect appliances to lighting circuits.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Where a lower rate was applied to electric power used for lighting circuits, lampholder plugs enabled the consumers to reduce their electricity costs.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Edison screw lampholder adaptors (for NEMA 1-15 plugs) are still commonly used in the Americas.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This Soviet plug, now rarely used, has pin dimensions and spacing equal to the Europlug, but lacks the insulation sleeves.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] It has a round body like the European CEE 7/2 or flat body with a round base like CEE 7/17.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins are parallel and do not converge.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The body is made of fire-resistant thermoset plastic.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The corresponding 6 A socket accepts the Europlug, but not others as the 4.5 mm holes are too small to accept the 4.8 mm pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6 or CEE 7/7 plugs.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] There were also moulded rubber plugs available for devices up to 16 A similar to CEE 7/17, but with a round base without any notches.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They could be altered to fit a CEE 7/5 or CEE 7/3 socket by cutting notches with a sharp knife.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Some appliances sold in the Soviet Union had a flat unearthed plug with an additional pass-through socket on the top, allowing a stacked arrangement of plugs.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins of the secondary plug (which lacked insulation sleeves) could not be inserted into the cylindrical sockets completely, leaving a 5 mm gap between the primary and secondary plugs.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The adaptors were mostly used for low power appliances (for example, connecting both a table lamp and a radio to a socket).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Compared to the standard BS 1363 plugs found in the UK, each pin is rotated 90 degrees.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This style of plug/socket was used by university laboratories (from batteries) and the BBC, and is still in use in parts of the London Underground for 110 V AC voltage supply.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s they were used for 240 V DC in the Power laboratory of the Electrical Engineering department of what was then University College, Cardiff.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Power was supplied by the public 240 V DC mains which remained available in addition to the 240 V AC mains until circa 1969, and thereafter from in-house rectifiers.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also used in the Ministry of Defence Main Building inside circuits powered from the standby generators to stop staff from plugging in unauthorized devices.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also known to be used in some British Rail offices for the same reason.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s, Italian firm BTicino introduced an alternative to the Europlug or CEI 23-16 connectors then in use, called Magic Security.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is rectangular with lateral key pins and indentations to maintain polarization and prevent insertion of a plug with different current ratings.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Three single-phase general purpose connectors were rated 10 A, 16 A and 20 A; and a three-phase industrial connector rated 10 A; all of them have different key-pin positioning so plugs and sockets cannot be mismatched.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is closed by a safety lid (bearing the word *Magic* on it) which can be opened only with an even pressure on its surface, thus preventing the insertion of objects (except the plug itself) inside the socket.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The contacts are positioned on both sides of the plug; the plug is energised only when it is inserted fully into the socket.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The system is not compatible with Italian CEI plugs, nor with Europlugs.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Appliances were never sold fitted with these security plugs, and the use of adaptors would defeat the safety features, so the supplied plugs had to be cut off and replaced with the security connector.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Even so, the *Magic* security system had some success at first because its enhanced safety features appealed to customers; standard connectors of the day were not considered safe enough.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The decline of the system occurred when safety lids similar to the Magic type were developed for standard sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Italy, the system was never definitively abandoned.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Though very rarely seen today, it is still marked as available in BTicino's catalogue, (except for the three-phase version, which stopped being produced in July 2011).
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Chile, 10 A Magic connectors are commonly used for computer/laboratory power networks, as well as for communications or data equipment.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This allows delicate electronics equipment to be connected to an independent circuit breaker, usually including a surge protector or an uninterruptible power supply backup.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The different style of plug makes it more difficult for office workers to connect computer equipment to a standard unprotected power line, or to overload the UPS by connecting other office appliances.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Iceland, Magic plugs were widely used in homes and businesses alongside Europlug and Schuko installations.
[src:mains-electricity/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Their installation in new homes was still quite common even in the late 1980s.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] An **adapter** or **adaptor** is a device that converts attributes of one electrical device or system to those of an otherwise incompatible device or system.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] Some modify power or signal attributes, while others merely adapt the physical form of one connector to another.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] Many countries with ties to Europe use 230-volt, 50 Hz AC mains electricity, using a variety of power plugs and sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] Difficulty arises when moving an electrical device between countries that use different sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] A passive electric power adapter, sometimes called a *travel plug* or *travel adapter*, allows using a plug from one region with a foreign socket.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] As other countries supply 120-volt, 60 Hz AC, using a travel adapter in a country with a different supply poses a safety hazard if the connected device does not support both input voltages.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] An AC-to-DC power supply adapts electricity from household mains voltage (either 120 or 230 volts AC) to low-voltage DC suitable for powering consumer electronics.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] Small, detached power supplies for consumer electronics are called *AC adapters*, or variously *power bricks*, *wall warts*, or *chargers*.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] A *host controller* connects a computer to a peripheral device, such as a storage device, network, or human interface device.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] As a host controller can also be viewed as bridging the protocols used on the buses between peripheral and computer, and internally to the computer, it is also called a *host bus adapter*.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] Likewise, specific types may be called adapters: a network interface controller may be called a *network adapter*, and a graphics card a *display adapter*.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] Adapters (often in the form of *dongles*) allow connecting a peripheral device with one plug to a different jack on the computer.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] They are often used to connect modern devices to a legacy port on an old system, or old devices to a modern port.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] Such adapters may be entirely passive, or contain active circuitry.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] One kind of serial port adapter enables connections between 25-contact and nine-contact connectors, but does not affect electrical power- and signalling-related attributes.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] HDMI is backward compatible with the single-channel digital video interface (DVI-D or DVI-I, but not DVI-A or dual-channel DVI).
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] When using an adapter or an asymmetric cable, no signal conversion is required, so video quality is not lost. “This means that DVI can be connected to an HDMI input using an adapter.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] DVI was an important step forward, introducing digital video.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] A separate cable to the audio output on the computer or sound card was required for that.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] Any DVI-HDMI adapter can function as an HDMI-DVI adapter (and vice versa).
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] Usually, the only limitation is the gender of the adapter connectors, as well as the gender of cables and connectors with which it is used.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] Features characteristic of HDMI, such as remote control and audio transmission, are not available on devices using the legacy DVI-D signal.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] However, many devices output HDMI via a DVI connector (for example, ATI 3000 series and NVIDIA GTX 200 graphics cards), and some multimedia displays can accept HDMI (including audio) through a DVI input.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] The exact capabilities beyond basic compatibility may vary.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] Adapters and active converters are also available for connecting HDMI to other video interfaces, including older analog formats as well as digital formats such as DisplayPort.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] Introduced in the 2000s, DisplayPort was designed to replace older standards such as VGA, DVI, and FPD-Link.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] Although it is not directly compatible with these formats, adapters are available for connecting to HDMI, DVI, VGA, and other interfaces.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] There are USB-CEC adapters that allow a computer to control devices supporting Consumer Electronics Control.
[src:mains-electricity/adapter] In software, an adapter is a piece of code that complies with an interface of an existing component while actually using another implementation.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The company's initial focus was driven by electrical lighting, as in 1881, Rathenau had acquired the rights to the electric light bulb at the International Exposition of Electricity in Paris.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] Using small power stations, his company introduced electrical lighting to cafés, restaurants, and theaters, despite the high costs and limitations.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] By the end of the 19th century, AEG had constructed 248 power stations, providing a total of 210,000 hp of electricity for lighting, tramways, and household devices.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] During the Second World War, AEG worked with the Nazi Party and benefited from forced labor in Nazi concentration camps.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] After the war, its headquarters moved to Frankfurt am Main.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In 1967, AEG joined with its subsidiary Telefunken.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In 1985, Daimler-Benz purchased AEG and wholly integrated the company in 1996.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The remains of AEG became part of Adtranz and Deutsche Aerospace.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] After acquiring the AEG household subsidiary AEG Hausgeräte in 1994, Electrolux obtained the rights to the AEG brand name in 2005, which it now uses on some of its products.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The AEG name is also licensed to various brand partners under the Electrolux Global Brand Licensing program.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In 1883, Emil Rathenau founded Deutsche Edison-Gesellschaft für angewandte Elektricität in Berlin.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In 1888, it was renamed as Allgemeine Elektricitäts-Gesellschaft.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] Initially producing electrical equipment (such as light bulbs, motors, and generators), the company soon became involved in AC electric-transmission systems.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In 1907, Peter Behrens was appointed as artistic consultant to AEG.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] This led to the creation of the company's initial corporate identity, with products and advertising sharing common design features.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The company expanded in the first half of the 20th century, and it is credited with a number of firsts and inventions in electrical engineering.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] During the same period, it entered the automobile and airplane markets.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] Electrical equipment for railways was produced during this time, beginning a long history of supplying the German railways with electrical equipment.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] During the Second World War, AEG joined with other large companies such as IG Farben, Thyssen, and Krupp in their support of the Nazis.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The company benefited from the use of large numbers of forced labourers, as well as concentration-camp prisoners, under inhuman conditions of work.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] After WWII, the company lost its businesses in the eastern part of Germany.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] After a merger in 1967, the company was renamed Allgemeine Elektricitäts-Gesellschaft AEG-Telefunken, and from 1979 on, only as AEG-Telefunken.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The company experienced financial difficulties during the 1970s, resulting in the sale of some assets.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In 1983, the consumer electronics division Telefunken Fernseh und Rundfunk was sold.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In 1985, the company retook the name AEG and the remainder of the company was acquired by Daimler-Benz; the parts that remained were primarily related to electric power distribution and electric motor technology.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] Under Daimler-Benz ownership, the former AEG companies eventually became part of the newly named Adtranz in 1995, and the AEG name was no longer used.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] Electrolux, which had already acquired the household subsidiary AEG Hausgeräte in 1994, now own the rights to use and license the AEG brand.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The company originated in 1882, when Emil Rathenau acquired licences to use some of Thomas Edison's lamp patents in Germany.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The Deutsche Edison Gesellschaft ("German Edison Company") was founded in 1883 with the financial backing of banks and private individuals, with Emil Rathenau as company director.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In 1884, Munich-born engineer Oskar von Miller (who later founded Deutsches Museum) joined the executive board.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The same year, the company entered negotiations with the Berlin Magistrat (the municipal body) to supply electricity to a large area from a central supply, which resulted in the formation of the Städtischen Elektrizitätswerke (A.G.StEW) ("City electricity works company (Berlin)") on 8 May 1884.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The original factory was located near Stettiner Bahnhof.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In 1887, the company acquired land in the Berlin-Gesundbrunnen area on which the Weddingsche Maschinenfabrik (founded by Wilhelm Wedding) was previously located.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In the same year, in addition to a restructuring and expansion of the production range, the AEG name was adopted.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In 1887, Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrowolsky joined the company as chief engineer, later becoming vice-director.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] His work on polyphase electric power led him to become the world's leading engineer in three-phase electric power systems at the end of the 1880s.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] This success marked one of beginnings of the general use of alternating current for electrification in Germany, and showed that distance transmission of electric power could be economically useful.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In the same year, the Stadtbahn Halle/Saale (City railway Halle–Saale) opened the first electric tram system (of notable size) in Germany.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] Tropp Paul began his work for the AEG from 1889/90 until 1893, and Franz Schwechten designed the facades of the Acker- und Hussitenstraße in 1894–95.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In 1894, the site of the former Berlin Viehmarktgasse (cattle market alley) was purchased.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] This had a railroad siding connecting to the Berlin rail network, but no rail connection existed between the two plants.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In 1895, an underground railway link between the two plots was built in a tunnel 270 meters long.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The tunnel was built by Siemens & Halske under the direction of C.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] Schwebel and Wilhelm Lauter, who were also connected in the building of what is now the Spree tunnel Stralau used by the U-Bahn.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] By 1889, AEG were known as specialists in the construction of industrial portable drilling machines, some of which were driven by flexible shafts from electric motors.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] AEG also developed a toothed-belt drive to reduce motor speed down to that required by machine tools.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In 1903, the competing radio companies AEG and Siemens & Halske merged, forming a joint subsidiary named Telefunken.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In 1907, architect Peter Behrens became an artistic adviser.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] Responsible for the design of all products, advertising, and architecture, he has since become considered as the world's first corporate designer.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] Behren's philosophy was to create a building which is solid, strong and simple in its structure.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] It is perfect for doing its job of producing large, heavy machinery.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The dimensions of the building were chosen to allow turbines to be transported above other machinery.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In the 1920s, AEG became a global supplier of electrical know-how and equipment.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In 1923, for example, it provided most of the essential materials and a team of engineers to oversee the electrification of British-ruled Palestine.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] British firms, at the time, could not compete with the prices of AEG.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The activity of the company soon extended to all areas of electrical power engineering, including electric lighting, electric power, electric railways, and electrochemical plants, as well as the construction of steam turbines, automobiles, cables, and cable materials.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] On 20 June 1915, founder Emil Rathenau died at age 77.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] AEG donated 60,000 Reichsmarks to the Nazi party after the Secret Meeting of 20 February 1933 at which the twin goals of complete power and national rearmament were explained by Hitler.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] They joined with other large companies, such as IG Farben, Thyssen and Krupp, in their support of the Nazis, especially in promoting re-armament of the Wehrmacht, Luftwaffe, and Kriegsmarine.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] During the war itself, they were to use large numbers of forced labourers as well as concentration camp prisoners, under inhuman conditions of work.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] AEG worked extensively with the Nazi party in occupied Poland.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] AEG was forced to relinquish Kabelwerk Krakow, a cable manufacturing plant, to the Nazi party.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] Kabelwerk Krakow was located in Krakow-Plaszow and used forced Jewish labor manufacturing cables from 1942 to 1944.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In 1943, AEG began to relocate goods and evacuate workers.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] Goods were relocated to various places, including Berlin and Sudetenland.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] When installing electric and lighting systems for the Waffen-SS training grounds in Dębica, AEG used forced labor from Jews placed in the Pustkow labor camp located in south east Poland.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] During World War II, an AEG factory near Riga used female slave labour.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] AEG was also contracted for the production of electrical equipment at Auschwitz concentration camp.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] 36 at the new sub-camp of Auschwitz III and also known as Monowitz, called "Arbeitslager Blechhammer".
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] Most of them would die in 1945 during the death marches and finally in Buchenwald.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] AEG was a major supplier of grips for P38 pistols manufactured by Walther Arms, Mauser, as well as on the early wartime Spreewerk P38s.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In an effort to express regret for its use of Jewish slave labour in World War II, AEG joined with Rheinmetall, Siemens, Krupp, and I G Farben to pay DEM75 million in reparations to the Jewish Claims Conference.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The steam and electric locomotive plant in Hennigsdorf (Fabriken Hennigsdorf) became a Volkseigener Betrieb (VEB) (people owned enterprise) as the Lokomotivbau Elektrotechnische Werke (LEW) ("electric locomotive works").
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The cable plant (Draht-, Kabel- und Metallwerk Oberspree) and apparatus factory (Apparatefabrik Treptow) and other facilities also lay in East Germany and became Sowjetische Aktiengesellschaft (SAG) (Soviet joint-stock companies).
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] Over 90% of assets in Berlin lay in the Russian occupied zone and were lost.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The headquarters for the non-expropriated parts of the company was moved first to Hamburg and then finally to Frankfurt am Main, the headquarters in Berlin having been destroyed.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In 1970, AEG-Telefunken had 178,000 employees worldwide, and was the 12th largest electrical company in the world.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The company was burdened by, among other things, unsuccessful projects such as an automated baggage conveyor system at Frankfurt Airport and nuclear powerplant construction.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In particular, the nuclear power plant at Würgassen, the commissioning of which was delayed by several years due to technical problems cost AEG hundreds of millions of DM.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] As a result, the company paid its last dividend in 1972.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The entertainment arm (Telefunken Fernseh und Rundfunk) headquartered in Hanover was sold.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] This was followed by the computer mainframe business (TR 4, TR 10, TR 440) (a partnership under the name Telefunken Computer with the company Nixdorf) was sold to Siemens.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The process computer (TR 84, TR 86, AEG 60–10, AEG 80–20, AEG 80–60) continued as *Geschäftsbereich Automatisierungstechnik* (after 1980 as ATM Computer).
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In 1975 the former Telefunken Headquarter at Berlin-Charlottenburg, Ernst-Reuter-Platz 7 was sold.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The building had been previously rented to Technische Universität Berlin.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In 1976, to circumvent the requirement of equal participation of employees in the supervisory board, Dr.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] Walter Cipa (Dipl.-Geol.) (AEG boss from 1976 to 1980) created four further companies as wholly owned joint stock companies in addition to the two household appliance companies.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In 1979 Allgemeine Elektricitäts-Gesellschaft AEG-Telefunken was renamed AEG-Telefunken by dropping the supplement "Allgemeine Elektricitäts-Gesellschaft", used since 1887.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In February 1980, Heinz Dürr became board Chairman (until 1990).
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In August 1982 a restructuring plan, backed with federal guarantees of 600 million DM and new bank loans of 275 million DM, fell apart at the first disagreement between the banks.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] A banking consortium provided an administrative loan of DM 1.1 billion to the AEG Group until June 1983; 400 million of which only to be available on a guarantee by the federal government.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] Not only was AEG-Telefunken affected, but also its subsidiaries Küppersbusch in Gelsenkirchen, Hermann Zanker Maschinenfabrik in Tübingen and Carl Neff in Bretten.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The Alno-Möbelwerke in Pfullendorf was taken over by the minority shareholders, and separated from the group.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The suppliers to AEG were affected and some filed for bankruptcy—including Becher & Co.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] Möbelfabriken in Bühlertann—with lack of continuity of company policy a factor.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The site at Brunnenstraße in the former Berlin district of Wedding was also sold, as were the firms AEG-Fabrik Essen and Bauknecht.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] AEG played an important role in the history of the German railways; the company was involved in the development and manufacture of the electrical parts of almost all German electric locomotive series and contributed to the introduction of electrical power in German railways.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] Additionally many steam locomotives were made in AEG factories.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In 1931 the company acquired Borsig and transferred the locomotive production to the AEG-Borsig works (Borsig Lokomotiv-Werke) from the Borsig plant in Tegel.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In 1948 the plant became VEB Lokomotivbau Elektrotechnische Werke.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] In addition to numerous electric locomotives produced for the DR steam locomotive production continued until 1954.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] When the Federal Republic of Germany began implementing AC propulsion systems AEG found itself in competition with Brown, Boveri & Cie.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The prototype DB Class E320 was built with Krupp as dual voltage (15 kV and 25 kV AC) test machine, the technology ultimately leading to locomotives such as DB Class 120 and ICE 1.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] Only after German reunification and the adoption of the LEW plant in Hennigsdorf did AEG's name return to whole locomotive manufacturing, but only for a short time.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] "AEG locomotives" became part of ABB Daimler-Benz Transportation (later ADtranz) and currently the technology developed in the past, in part, now enables Alstom to build the very successful Traxx series of locomotives.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] Between 1992 to 1994, AEG built 96 metro cars for Shanghai Metro.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] AEG manufactured a range of aircraft from 1912 to 1918.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The first aircraft in 1912 was of wooden construction and modeled after the Wright brothers biplane.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] It had a wingspan of 17.5 m (57 ft 5 in); was powered by an eight-cylinder engine producing 75 hp; unloaded weight was 850 kg; and could attain a speed of 65 km/h (40 mph).
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] From 1912, the construction of airplanes proceeded in mixed wood and steel tube construction with fabric covering.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] One of the planes designed and built was a *Riesenflugzeug* ("giant aircraft") AEG R.I.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] This aircraft was powered by four 260 hp (190 kW) Mercedes D.IVa engines linked to a combination leather cone and dog clutch.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The first flight tests were satisfactory, but on 3 September 1918, the R.I broke up in the air killing its seven crewmen.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The most successful in terms of production figures of all the AEG aircraft designs was that of the G.IV *Grossflugzeuge* ("large aircraft") heavy tactical bomber, of which one still survives of the 320 built, as the sole surviving World War One German multi-engine bomber.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] During the Second World War AEG produced machines for reconnaissance purposes, including a helicopter platform driven by an AC motor.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] This was a tethered craft that could not fly freely; the power supply was carried by three cables from the ground.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] The machine reached an altitude of 300 m.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] AEG bought Kühlstein in 1902, founding the division *Neue Automobil Gesellschaft* (New Automobile Company), to make cars.
[src:mains-electricity/aeg-german-company] AEG withdrew from car production in 1908.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] There are various types of air conditioners.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In hot weather, air conditioning can prevent heat stroke, dehydration due to excessive sweating, electrolyte imbalance, kidney failure, and other issues due to hyperthermia.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] An estimated 190,000 heat-related deaths are averted annually owing to air conditioning.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Air conditioners increase productivity in hot climates, and historians rank air conditioning as a key factor that shaped postwar metropolitan growth, alongside highways, automobiles, shopping malls, and suburban housing.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] As of 2022, air conditioning used about 7% of global electricity and emitted 3% of greenhouse gas.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Air conditioners, which typically use vapor-compression refrigeration, range in size from small units used in vehicles or single rooms to massive units that can cool large buildings.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Air source heat pumps, which can be used for heating as well as cooling, are becoming increasingly common in cooler climates.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] According to the International Energy Agency (IEA) 1.6 billion air conditioning units were used globally in 2016.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The United Nations has called for the technology to be made more sustainable to mitigate climate change and for the use of alternatives, such as passive cooling, evaporative cooling, selective shading, windcatchers, and thermal insulation.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Air conditioning dates back to prehistory.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Double-walled living quarters, with a gap between the two walls to encourage air flow, were found in the ancient city of Hamoukar, in modern Syria.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Ancient Egyptian buildings also used a wide variety of passive air-conditioning techniques.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] These became widespread from the Iberian Peninsula through North Africa, the Middle East, and Northern India.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Passive techniques remained widespread until the 20th century when they fell out of fashion and were replaced by powered air conditioning.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Using information from engineering studies of traditional buildings, passive techniques are being revived and modified for 21st-century architectural designs.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Air conditioners allow the building's indoor environment to remain relatively constant, largely independent of changes in external weather conditions and internal heat loads.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] They also enable deep plan buildings to be created and have allowed people to live comfortably in hotter parts of the world.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In 1558, Giambattista della Porta described a method of chilling ice to temperatures far below its freezing point by mixing it with potassium nitrate (then called "nitre") in his popular science book *Natural Magic*.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In 1620, Cornelis Drebbel demonstrated "Turning Summer into Winter" for James I of England, chilling part of the Great Hall of Westminster Abbey with an apparatus of troughs and vats.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In 1758, Benjamin Franklin and John Hadley, a chemistry professor at the University of Cambridge, conducted experiments applying the principle of evaporation as a means to cool an object rapidly.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Franklin and Hadley confirmed that the evaporation of highly volatile liquids (such as alcohol and ether) could be used to drive down the temperature of an object past the freezing point of water.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] They experimented with the bulb of a mercury-in-glass thermometer as their object.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] They used a bellows to speed up the evaporation.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] They lowered the temperature of the thermometer bulb down to −14 °C (7 °F) while the ambient temperature was 18 °C (64 °F).
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Franklin noted that soon after they passed the freezing point of water 0 °C (32 °F), a thin film of ice formed on the surface of the thermometer's bulb and that the ice mass was about 6 mm (1⁄4 in) thick when they stopped the experiment upon reaching −14 °C (7 °F).
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The 19th century included many developments in compression technology.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In 1820, English scientist and inventor Michael Faraday discovered that compressing and liquefying ammonia could chill air when the liquefied ammonia was allowed to evaporate.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In 1842, Florida physician John Gorrie used compressor technology to create ice, which he used to cool air for his patients in his hospital in Apalachicola, Florida.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] He hoped to eventually use his ice-making machine to regulate the temperature of buildings.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] He envisioned centralized air conditioning that could cool entire cities.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Gorrie was granted a patent in 1851, but following the death of his main backer, he was not able to realize his invention.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In 1851, James Harrison created the first mechanical ice-making machine in Geelong, Australia, and was granted a patent for an ether vapor-compression refrigeration system in 1855 that produced three tons of ice per day.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In 1860, Harrison established a second ice company.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] He later entered the debate over competing against the American advantage of ice-refrigerated beef sales to the United Kingdom.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] This innovation made the systems more compact and suitable for urban environments.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] By 1896, his factory produced 'dry air cooling apparatuses' specifically designed for the cooling and dehumidification of hospitals, theaters, large public halls, and even residential rooms, several years before the widespread commercialization of modern air conditioning.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] This system operated by using an electric motor-driven ammonia compressor to chill a secondary refrigerant, typically brine (salt water).
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] This cold brine was circulated through pipes to a 'dry air cooling unit' (a precursor to the modern air handler), where a fan forced ambient air over the chilled coils.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] This process not only lowered the temperature but also dehumidified the air by condensing moisture on the cold surfaces.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Electricity made the development of effective units possible.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Carrier built what is considered the first modern electrical air conditioning unit.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In 1902, he installed his first air-conditioning system in the Sackett-Wilhelms Lithographing & Publishing Company in Brooklyn, New York.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] He patented "air conditioning" in 1906, and by 1914, the first domestic (or "residential") air conditioner was installed.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] His invention controlled both the temperature and humidity, which helped maintain consistent paper dimensions and ink alignment at the printing plant.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Later, together with six other employees, Carrier formed The Carrier Air Conditioning Company of America, a business that in 2020, employed 53,000 people and was valued at $18.6 billion.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Cramer of Charlotte, North Carolina, was exploring ways to add moisture to the air in his textile mill.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Cramer coined the term "air conditioning" in a patent claim which he filed that year, where he suggested that air conditioning was analogous to "water conditioning", then a well-known process for making textiles easier to process.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] He combined moisture with ventilation to "condition" and change the air in the factories, thus controlling the humidity that is necessary in textile plants.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Willis Carrier adopted the term and incorporated it into the name of his company.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Domestic air conditioning soon took off.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In 1914, the first domestic air conditioning was installed in Minneapolis in the home of Charles Gilbert Gates.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] It is, however, possible that the considerable device (c.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Sherman developed what would become the most common type of individual room air conditioner: one designed to sit on a window ledge.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The units went on sale in 1932 at US$10,000 to $50,000 (the equivalent of $200,000 to $1,200,000 in 2025.) A year later, the first air conditioning systems for cars were offered for sale.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Chrysler Motors introduced the first practical semi-portable air conditioning unit in 1935, and Packard became the first automobile manufacturer to offer an air conditioning unit in its cars in 1939.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Innovations in the latter half of the 20th century allowed more ubiquitous air conditioner use.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In 1945, Robert Sherman of Lynn, Massachusetts, invented a portable, in-window air conditioner that cooled, heated, humidified, dehumidified, and filtered the air.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The first inverter air conditioners were released in 1980–1981.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In 1954, Ned Cole, a 1939 architecture graduate from the University of Texas at Austin, developed the first experimental "suburb" with inbuilt air conditioning in each house.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In addition, researchers from UT's Health Service and Psychology Department studied the effects on the "artificially cooled humans." One of the more amusing discoveries was that each family reported being troubled with scorpions, the leading theory being that scorpions sought cool, shady places.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Other reported changes in lifestyle were that mothers baked more, families ate heavier foods, and they were more apt to choose hot drinks.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Air conditioner adoption tends to increase above around $10,000 (circa 2021) annual household income in warmer areas.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Global GDP growth explains around 85% of increased air condition adoption by 2050, while the remaining 15% can be explained by climate change.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The urban heat island effect was first scientifically noted by Luke Howard in the 1810s, who described London being several degrees warmer than its rural surroundings at night.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The phenomenon gained attention in the late 1960s, mainly in Japan and North America.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] From the late 1980s to early 2010s, studies began to link air conditioners to the urban heat island effect.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The phenomenon was observed in various cities such as Tokyo and Houston.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] As of 2016, an estimated 1.6 billion air conditioning units were used worldwide, with over half of them in China and the United States, and with a total cooling capacity of 11,675 gigawatts.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The International Energy Agency predicted in 2018 that the number of air conditioning units would grow to around 4 billion units by 2050 and that the total cooling capacity would grow to around 23,000 GW, with the biggest increases in India and China.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Between 1995 and 2004, the proportion of urban households in China with air conditioners increased from 8% to 70%.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Between 2010 and 2023, air conditioner use in India tripled to 24 units per 100 households, with the most ownership in Haryana, Chandigarh, Rajasthan, and Delhi and the least in Meghalaya, Tripura, Manipur, and Himachal Pradesh.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] As of 2015, nearly 100 million homes in the United States, or about 87% of US households, had air conditioning systems.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In 2019, it was estimated that 90% of new single-family homes constructed in the US included air conditioning, ranging from 99% in the South to 62% in the West.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] As of 2025, roughly half of homes in Italy, 40 percent of homes in Spain, and 20 to 25 percent of homes in France had air conditioning.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Cooling in traditional air conditioner systems is accomplished using the vapor-compression cycle, which uses a refrigerant's forced circulation and phase change between gas and liquid to transfer heat.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The vapor-compression cycle can occur within a unitary, or packaged piece of equipment, or within a chiller that is connected to terminal cooling equipment (such as a fan coil unit in an air handler) on its evaporator side and heat rejection equipment such as a cooling tower on its condenser side.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] An air source heat pump shares many components with an air conditioning system, but includes a reversing valve, which allows the unit to be used to heat as well as cool a space.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Air conditioning equipment will reduce the absolute humidity of the air processed by the system if the surface of the evaporator coil is significantly cooler than the dew point of the surrounding air.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] An air conditioner designed for an occupied space will typically achieve a 30% to 60% relative humidity in the occupied space.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Most modern air-conditioning systems feature a dehumidification mode, in which the compressor runs.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] At the same time, the fan is slowed to reduce the evaporator temperature and condense more water.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Free cooling can sometimes be selected when the external air is cooler than the internal air.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In this case, the compressor does not need to be used, resulting in high cooling efficiencies for these times.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] This may also be combined with seasonal thermal energy storage.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Some air conditioning systems can reverse the refrigeration cycle and act as an air source heat pump, thus heating instead of cooling the indoor environment.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] They are also commonly referred to as "reverse cycle air conditioners".
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The heat pump is significantly more energy-efficient than electric resistance heating, because it moves energy from air or groundwater to the heated space and the heat from purchased electrical energy.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] When the heat pump is in heating mode, the indoor evaporator coil switches roles and becomes the condenser coil, producing heat and the outdoor condenser unit also switches roles to serve as the evaporator and discharges cold air (colder than the ambient outdoor air).
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Most air source heat pumps become less efficient in outdoor temperatures lower than 4 °C or 40 °F.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] This is partly because ice forms on the outdoor unit's heat exchanger coil, which blocks air flow over the coil.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] To compensate for this, the heat pump system must temporarily switch back into the regular air conditioning mode to switch the outdoor evaporator coil back to being the condenser coil, so it can heat up and defrost.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Therefore, some heat pump systems will have electric resistance heating in the indoor air path that is activated only in this mode to compensate for the temporary indoor air cooling, which would otherwise be uncomfortable in the winter.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Newer models have improved cold-weather performance, with efficient heating capacity down to −14 °F (−26 °C).
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] However, there is always a chance that the humidity that condenses on the heat exchanger of the outdoor unit could freeze, even in models that have improved cold-weather performance, requiring a defrosting cycle to be performed.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In this case, the heat pump is used efficiently during milder temperatures, and the system is switched to the conventional heat source when the outdoor temperature is lower.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The coefficient of performance (COP) of an air conditioning system is a ratio of useful heating or cooling provided to the work required.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Higher COPs equate to lower operating costs.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The COP usually exceeds 1; however, the exact value is highly dependent on operating conditions, especially absolute temperature and relative temperature between sink and system, and is often graphed or averaged against expected conditions.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Air conditioner equipment power in the U.S. is often described in terms of "tons of refrigeration", with each approximately equal to the cooling power of one short ton (2,000 pounds (910 kg) of ice melting in a 24-hour period.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The value is equal to 12,000 BTUIT per hour, or 3,517 watts.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Residential central air systems are usually from 1 to 5 tons (3.5 to 18 kW) in capacity.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The efficiency of air conditioners is often rated by the seasonal energy efficiency ratio (SEER), which is defined by the Air Conditioning, Heating and Refrigeration Institute in its 2008 standard AHRI 210/240, *Performance Rating of Unitary Air-Conditioning and Air-Source Heat Pump Equipment*.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] A similar standard is the European seasonal energy efficiency ratio (ESEER).
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Efficiency is strongly affected by the humidity of the air to be cooled.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Dehumidifying the air before attempting to cool it can reduce subsequent cooling costs by as much as 90 percent.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Thus, reducing dehumidifying costs can materially affect overall air conditioning costs.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] This type of controller uses an infrared LED to relay commands from a remote control to the air conditioner.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The output of the infrared LED (like that of any infrared remote) is invisible to the human eye because its wavelength is beyond the range of visible light (940 nm).
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] This system is commonly used on mini-split air conditioners because it is simple and portable.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Some window and ducted central air conditioners uses it as well.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] A wired controller, also called a "wired thermostat," is a device that controls an air conditioner by switching heating or cooling on or off.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] It uses different sensors to measure temperatures and actuate control operations.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Mechanical thermostats commonly use bimetallic strips, converting a temperature change into mechanical displacement, to actuate control of the air conditioner.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Electronic thermostats, instead, use a thermistor or other semiconductor sensor, processing temperature change as electronic signals to control the air conditioner.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] These controllers are usually used in apartments, hospitals, offices and hotel rooms, because they are permanently installed into a wall and hard-wired directly into the air conditioner unit, eliminating the need for batteries.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Ductless systems (often mini-split, though there are now ducted mini-split) typically supply conditioned and heated air to a single or a few rooms of a building, without ducts and in a decentralized manner.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Multi-zone or multi-split systems are a common application of ductless systems and allow up to eight rooms (zones or locations) to be conditioned independently from each other, each with its indoor unit and simultaneously from a single outdoor unit.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The first mini-split system was sold in 1961 by Toshiba in Japan, and the first wall-mounted mini-split air conditioner was sold in 1968 in Japan by Mitsubishi Electric, where small home sizes motivated their development.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The Mitsubishi model was the first air conditioner with a cross-flow fan.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In 1969, the first mini-split air conditioner was sold in the US.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Multi-zone ductless systems were invented by Daikin in 1973, and variable refrigerant flow systems (which can be thought of as larger multi-split systems) were also invented by Daikin in 1982.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The outdoor and indoor units can be spread across the building.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Variable refrigerant flow indoor units can also be turned off individually in unused spaces.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The lower start-up power of VRF's DC inverter compressors and their inherent DC power requirements also allow VRF solar-powered heat pumps to be run using DC-providing solar panels.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Split-system central air conditioners consist of two heat exchangers, an outside unit (the condenser) from which heat is rejected to the environment and an internal heat exchanger (the evaporator, or Fan Coil Unit, FCU) with the piped refrigerant being circulated between the two.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The FCU is then connected to the spaces to be cooled by ventilation ducts.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Floor standing air conditioners are similar to this type of air conditioner but sit within spaces that need cooling.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The chilled water is cooled by chillers in the plant, which uses a refrigeration cycle to cool water, often transferring its heat to the atmosphere even in liquid-cooled chillers through the use of cooling towers.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] A portable system has an indoor unit on wheels connected to an outdoor unit via flexible pipes, similar to a permanently fixed installed unit (such as a ductless split air conditioner).
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Hose systems, which can be *monoblock* or *air-to-air*, are vented to the outside via air ducts.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The *monoblock* type collects the water in a bucket or tray and stops when full.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The *air-to-air* type re-evaporates the water, discharges it through the ducted hose, and can run continuously.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Many but not all portable units draw indoor air and expel it outdoors through a single duct, negatively impacting their overall cooling efficiency.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Many portable air conditioners come with heat as well as a dehumidification function.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The packaged terminal air conditioner (PTAC), through-the-wall, and window air conditioners are similar.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] These units are installed on a window frame or on a wall opening.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The unit usually has an internal partition separating its indoor and outdoor sides, which contain the unit's condenser and evaporator, respectively.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] PTAC systems may be adapted to provide heating in cold weather, either directly by using an electric strip, gas, or other heaters, or by reversing the refrigerant flow to heat the interior and draw heat from the exterior air, converting the air conditioner into a heat pump.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] They may be installed in a wall opening with the help of a special sleeve on the wall and a custom grill that is flush with the wall and window air conditioners can also be installed in a window, but without a custom grill.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Packaged air conditioners (also known as self-contained units) are central systems that integrate into a single housing all the components of a split central system, and deliver air, possibly through ducts, to the spaces to be cooled.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Depending on their construction the units may be kept outdoors or indoors; draw the air to be conditioned from inside or outside a building and be water or air-cooled.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Often, outdoor units are air-cooled while indoor units are liquid-cooled using a cooling tower.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] This compressor consists of a crankcase, crankshaft, piston rod, piston, piston ring, cylinder head and valves.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] This compressor uses two interleaving scrolls to compress the refrigerant. it consists of one fixed and one orbiting scrolls.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] This type of compressor is more efficient because it has 70 percent less moving parts than a reciprocating compressor.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] This compressor use two very closely meshing spiral rotors to compress the gas.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The gas enters at the suction side and moves through the threads as the screws rotate.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The meshing rotors force the gas through the compressor, and the gas exits at the end of the screws.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The working area is the inter-lobe volume between the male and female rotors.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] It is larger at the intake end, and decreases along the length of the rotors until the exhaust port.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] This change in volume is the compression.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] There are several ways to modulate the cooling capacity in refrigeration or air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The most common in air conditioning are: on-off cycling, hot gas bypass, use or not of liquid injection, manifold configurations of multiple compressors, mechanical modulation (also called digital), and inverter technology.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Hot gas bypass involves injecting a quantity of gas from discharge to the suction side.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The compressor will keep operating at the same speed, but due to the bypass, the refrigerant mass flow circulating with the system is reduced, and thus the cooling capacity is also reduced.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] This naturally causes the compressor to run uselessly during the periods when the bypass is operating.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The turn down capacity varies between 0 and 100%.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Several compressors can be installed in the system to provide the peak cooling capacity.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Each compressor can run or not in order to stage the cooling capacity of the unit.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The turn down capacity is either 0/33/66 or 100% for a trio configuration and either 0/50 or 100% for a tandem.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] This internal mechanical capacity modulation is based on periodic compression process with a control valve, the two scroll set move apart stopping the compression for a given time period.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] This method varies refrigerant flow by changing the average time of compression, but not the actual speed of the motor.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Despite an excellent turndown ratio – from 10 to 100% of the cooling capacity, mechanically modulated scrolls have high energy consumption as the motor continuously runs.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] This system uses a variable-frequency drive (also called an Inverter) to control the speed of the compressor.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The refrigerant flow rate is changed by the change in the speed of the compressor.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The turn down ratio depends on the system configuration and manufacturer.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] It modulates from 15 or 25% up to 100% at full capacity with a single inverter from 12 to 100% with a hybrid tandem.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] This method is the most efficient way to modulate an air conditioner's capacity.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] It is up to 58% more efficient than a fixed speed system.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Heat waves are the most lethal type of weather phenomenon in the United States.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] A 2020 study found that areas with lower use of air conditioning correlated with higher rates of heat-related mortality and hospitalizations.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The August 2003 France heatwave resulted in approximately 15,000 deaths, where 80% of the victims were over 75 years old.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In response, the French government required all retirement homes to have at least one air-conditioned room at 25 °C (77 °F) per floor during heatwaves.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] A 2021 report estimated that around 345,000 people aged 65 and older died in 2019 from the heat, which is preventable with air conditioning.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Air conditioning (including filtration, humidification, cooling and disinfection) can be used to provide a clean, safe, hypoallergenic atmosphere in hospital operating rooms and other environments where proper atmosphere is critical to patient safety and well-being.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] It is sometimes recommended for home use by people with allergies, especially mold.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] However, poorly maintained water cooling towers can promote the growth and spread of microorganisms such as *Legionella pneumophila*, the infectious agent responsible for Legionnaires' disease.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] As long as the cooling tower is kept clean (usually by means of a chlorine treatment), these health hazards can be avoided or reduced.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The state of New York has codified requirements for registration, maintenance, and testing of cooling towers to protect against Legionella.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] First designed to benefit targeted industries such as the press as well as large factories, the invention quickly spread to public agencies and administrations with studies with claims of increased productivity close to 24% in places equipped with air conditioning.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Air conditioning contributed to the economic development of the American South after the 1950s by enabling industrial activities in hot climates and supporting the expansion of white-collar work in cooled office spaces.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] It also influenced urban sprawl and commuting patterns, as air-conditioned vehicles made suburban development more viable.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Historians rank air conditioning among key factors shaping postwar metropolitan growth, alongside highways, automobiles, shopping malls, and suburban housing.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Air conditioning caused various shifts in demography, notably that of the United States starting from the 1970s.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In the US, the birth rate was lower in the spring than during other seasons until the 1970s but this difference then declined since then.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] As of 2007, the Sun Belt contained 30% of the total US population while it was inhabited by 24% of Americans at the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Moreover, the summer mortality rate in the US, which had been higher in regions subject to a heat wave during the summer, also evened out.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The spread of the use of air conditioning acts as a main driver for the growth of global demand of electricity.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] A 2020 survey found that an estimated 88% of all US households use AC, increasing to 93% when solely looking at homes built between 2010 and 2020.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Air conditioning used about 7% of global electricity in 2022, and emitted 3% of greenhouse gas.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] There is some push to increase the energy efficiency of air conditioners.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP) and the IEA found that if air conditioners could be twice as effective as now, 460 billion tons of GHG could be cut over 40 years.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The UNEP and IEA also recommended legislation to decrease the use of hydrofluorocarbons, better building insulation, and more sustainable temperature-controlled food supply chains going forward.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Refrigerants have also caused and continue to cause serious environmental issues, including ozone depletion and climate change, as several countries have not yet ratified the Kigali Amendment to reduce the consumption and production of hydrofluorocarbons.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] CFCs and HCFCs refrigerants such as R-12 and R-22, respectively, used within air conditioners have caused damage to the ozone layer, and hydrofluorocarbon refrigerants such as R-410A and R-404A, which were designed to replace CFCs and HCFCs, are instead exacerbating climate change.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Both issues happen due to the venting of refrigerant to the atmosphere, such as during repairs.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] HFO refrigerants, used in some if not most new equipment, solve both issues with an ozone damage potential (ODP) of zero and a much lower global warming potential (GWP) in the single or double digits vs. the three or four digits of hydrofluorocarbons.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Hydrofluorocarbons would have raised global temperatures by around 0.3–0.5 °C (0.5–0.9 °F) by 2100 without the Kigali Amendment.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] With the Kigali Amendment, the increase of global temperatures by 2100 due to hydrofluorocarbons is predicted to be around 0.06 °C (0.1 °F).
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Air conditioning units also contribute to pollution as they are difficult to disassemble or repair.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Separating metal and plastic at the end of a unit's life cycle is also costly and not practical, meaning units are frequently disposed of.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Several journalists say it is an *air conditioning paradox* that arises from the usage of air conditioners to adapt to the effects of climate change, leading to higher energy consumption and heat generation as a byproduct, thereby exacerbating the problem.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Alternatives are currently being explored by governments and researchers, such as more energy-efficient systems, passive cooling techniques, and the development of low-GWP refrigerants.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] However, balancing the demand for cooling with the need to reduce carbon footprints remains a complex and pressing issue.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] As renewable energy becomes cheaper and more popular, the energy source of air conditioners is shifting towards more renewable energy sources.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The danger of high-GWP refrigerants, such as HFCs, escaping into the atmosphere and trapping heat can be mitigated through development of low-GWP refrigerants.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Socioeconomic groups with a household income below around $10,000 (circa 2021) tend to have a low air conditioning adoption, which worsens heat-related mortality.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The lack of cooling can be hazardous, as areas with lower use of air conditioning correlate with higher rates of heat-related mortality and hospitalizations.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Premature mortality in New York City is projected to grow between 47% and 95% in 30 years, with lower-income and vulnerable populations most at risk.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Studies on the correlation between heat-related mortality and hospitalizations and living in low socioeconomic locations can be traced in Phoenix, Arizona, Hong Kong, China, Japan, and Italy.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Additionally, costs concerning health care can act as another barrier, as the lack of private health insurance during a 2009 heat wave in Australia, was associated with heat-related hospitalization.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] A study examining the US cities of Chicago, Detroit, Minneapolis, and Pittsburgh found that black households were half as likely to have central air conditioning units when compared to their white counterparts.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Especially in cities, redlining and other historical practices mean that racial disparities are also played out in heat islands, increasing temperatures in certain parts of the city.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] This is due to heat-absorbing building materials and pavements and lack of vegetation and shade coverage.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] There have been initiatives that provide cooling solutions to low-income communities, such as public cooling spaces.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Cooling has allowed for growth of indoor home space and encouraged people, including children, to stay indoors more often.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] It has also created uniformity of different geographical areas and climate zones.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Alternatives to continual air conditioning include passive cooling, passive solar cooling, natural ventilation, operating shades to reduce solar gain, using trees, architectural shades, windows (and using window coatings) to reduce solar gain.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Buildings designed with passive air conditioning are generally less expensive to construct and maintain than buildings with conventional HVAC systems with lower energy demands.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] While tens of air changes per hour, and cooling of tens of degrees, can be achieved with passive methods, site-specific microclimate must be taken into account, complicating building design.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Many techniques can be used to increase comfort and reduce the temperature in buildings.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] These include evaporative cooling, selective shading, wind, thermal convection, and heat storage.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Passive ventilation is the process of supplying air to and removing air from an indoor space without using mechanical systems.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] It refers to the flow of external air to an indoor space as a result of pressure differences arising from natural forces.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] There are two types of natural ventilation occurring in buildings: *wind driven ventilation* and *buoyancy-driven ventilation*.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Wind driven ventilation arises from the different pressures created by wind around a building or structure, and openings being formed on the perimeter which then permit flow through the building.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Buoyancy-driven ventilation occurs as a result of the directional buoyancy force that results from temperature differences between the interior and exterior.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Since the internal heat gains which create temperature differences between the interior and exterior are created by natural processes, including the heat from people, and wind effects are variable, naturally ventilated buildings are sometimes called "breathing buildings".
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Natural solutions do not require energy for cooling purposes, and are therefore a very attractive solution.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Many ways to achieve this have been explored.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The structure of a building can help dissipate heat.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] For example, in Zimbabwe, Eastgate Development cut its energy use by 90% by utilizing termite mound inspired structures.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Coverage of windows can help reduce internal heat gain from sunlight.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Department of Energy estimates that window awnings can lower internal heat gain from sunlight by up to 77%.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The coating of roofs have also seen great success.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In the United States, painting roofs white has been shown to lower roof temperatures by as much as 30 °C.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Meanwhile, in China, a project involving the installation of green roofs — roofs covered with vegetation — not only reduced the cooling demands of buildings, but also lowered the average land surface temperature in the area by 0.91 °C.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Planting trees can also help mitigate the heat island effect.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] A study in Europe discovered that tree cover can reduce land surface temperatures in cities by as much as 12 °C during the summer.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In the United States, another study found that when tree cover reaches 40%, ground-level temperatures were lowered by nearly 6 °C.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Passive cooling is a building design approach that focuses on heat gain control and heat dissipation in a building in order to improve the indoor thermal comfort with low or no energy consumption.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] This approach works either by preventing heat from entering the interior (heat gain prevention) or by removing heat from the building (natural cooling).
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Natural cooling utilizes on-site energy, available from the natural environment, combined with the architectural design of building components (e.g. building envelope), rather than mechanical systems to dissipate heat.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Therefore, natural cooling depends not only on the architectural design of the building but on how the site's natural resources are used as heat sinks (i.e. everything that absorbs or dissipates heat).
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Examples of on-site heat sinks are the upper atmosphere (night sky), the outdoor air (wind), and the earth/soil.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Passive cooling is an important tool for design of buildings for climate change adaptation – reducing dependency on energy-intensive air conditioning in warming environments.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Passive daytime radiative cooling (PDRC) surfaces reflect incoming solar radiation and heat back into outer space through the infrared window for cooling during the daytime.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Daytime radiative cooling became possible with the ability to suppress solar heating using photonic structures, which emerged through a study by Raman et al.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] PDRCs can come in a variety of forms, including paint coatings and films, that are designed to be high in solar reflectance and thermal emittance.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] PDRC applications on building roofs and envelopes have demonstrated significant decreases in energy consumption and costs.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In suburban single-family residential areas, PDRC application on roofs can potentially lower energy costs by 26% to 46%.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] PDRCs are predicted to show a market size of ~$27 billion for indoor space cooling by 2025 and have undergone a surge in research and development since the 2010s.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Hand fans have existed since prehistory.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Large human-powered fans built into buildings include the punkah.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The 2nd-century Chinese inventor Ding Huan of the Han dynasty invented a rotary fan for air conditioning, with seven wheels 3 m (10 ft) in diameter and manually powered by prisoners.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] 712–762) of the Tang dynasty (618–907) had the Cool Hall (*Liang Dian* 涼殿) built in the imperial palace, which the *Tang Yulin* describes as having water-powered fan wheels for air conditioning as well as rising jet streams of water from fountains.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] During the subsequent Song dynasty (960–1279), written sources mentioned the air conditioning rotary fan as even more widely used.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In areas that are cold at night or in winter, heat storage is used.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Heat may be stored in earth or masonry; air is drawn past the masonry to heat or cool it.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In areas that are below freezing at night in winter, snow and ice can be collected and stored in ice houses for later use in cooling.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] This technique is over 3,700 years old in the Middle East.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Harvesting outdoor ice during winter and transporting and storing for use in summer was practiced by wealthy Europeans in the early 1600s, and became popular in Europe and the Americas towards the end of the 1600s.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] This practice was replaced by mechanical compression-cycle icemakers.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] In dry, hot climates, the evaporative cooling effect may be used by placing water at the air intake, such that the draft draws air over water and then into the house.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] For this reason, it is sometimes said that the fountain, in the architecture of hot, arid climates, is like the fireplace in the architecture of cold climates.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Evaporative cooling also makes the air more humid, which can be beneficial in a dry desert climate.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] Evaporative coolers tend to feel as if they are not working during times of high humidity, when there is not much dry air with which the coolers can work to make the air as cool as possible for dwelling occupants.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] There is a longstanding political controversy about air conditioning, particularly in the nations of Europe, where the technology is relatively unadopted.
[src:mains-electricity/air-conditioning] The strongest opposition generally originates from environmentalists, European federalists, and left-wing parties, while supporters tend to be from the political right.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:mains-electricity/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] The **American National Standards Institute** (**ANSI**) is a private nonprofit organization that oversees the development of voluntary consensus standards for products, services, processes, systems, and personnel in the United States.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] The organization also coordinates U.S. standards with international standards so that American products can be used worldwide.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI accredits standards that are developed by representatives of other standards organizations, government agencies, consumer groups, companies, and others.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] These standards ensure that the characteristics and performance of products are consistent, that people use the same definitions and terms, and that products are tested the same way.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI also accredits standards developing organizations (SDOs) and provides a searchable directory of accredited standards developers (ASDs).
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI similarly accredits organizations that carry out product or personnel certification in accordance with requirements defined in international standards.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] The organization's headquarters are in Washington, D.C.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's operations office is located in New York City.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] The ANSI annual operating budget is funded by the sale of publications, membership dues and fees, accreditation services, fee-based programs, and international standards programs.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] Many ANSI regulations are incorporated by reference into United States federal statutes (i.e. by OSHA regulations referring to individual ANSI specifications).
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI does not make these standards publicly available, and charges money for access to these documents; it further claims that it is copyright infringement for them to be provided to the public by others free of charge.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] These assertions have been the subject of criticism and litigation.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI was most likely formed in 1918, when five engineering societies and three government agencies founded the **American Engineering Standards Committee** (**AESC**).
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] In 1928, the AESC became the **American Standards Association** (**ASA**).
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] In 1966, the ASA was reorganized and became the **United States of America Standards Institute** (**USASI**).
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] In February 1969, Ralph Nader harshly criticized the USASI in public remarks as "manifestly deceptive" in several different ways.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] He specifically attacked the name USASI as improperly implying some kind of official connection with the federal government of the United States.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] had been members of the United Engineering Society (UES).
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] At the behest of the AIEE, they invited the U.S. government Departments of War, Navy (combined in 1947 to become the Department of Defense or DOD) and Commerce to join in founding a national standards organization.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] According to Adam Stanton, the first permanent secretary and head of staff in 1919, AESC started as an ambitious program and little else.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] Staff for the first year consisted of one executive, Clifford B.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] LePage, who was on loan from a founding member, ASME.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] An annual budget of $7,500 was provided by the founding bodies.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] In 1931, the organization (renamed ASA in 1928) became affiliated with the U.S.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] National Committee of the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), which had been formed in 1904 to develop electrical and electronics standards.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's members are government agencies, organizations, academic and international bodies, and individuals.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] In total, the Institute represents the interests of more than 270,000 companies and organizations and 30 million professionals worldwide.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's market-driven, decentralized approach has been criticized in comparison with more planned and organized international approaches to standardization.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] Although ANSI itself does not develop standards, the Institute oversees the development and use of standards by accrediting the procedures of standards developing organizations.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI accreditation signifies that the procedures used by standards developing organizations meet the institute's requirements for openness, balance, consensus, and due process.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI also designates specific standards as American National Standards, or ANS, when the Institute determines that the standards were developed in an environment that is equitable, accessible and responsive to the requirements of various stakeholders.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] Voluntary consensus standards quicken the market acceptance of products while making clear how to improve the safety of those products for the protection of consumers.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] There are approximately 9,500 American National Standards that carry the ANSI designation.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] The institute is the official U.S. representative to the two major international standards organizations, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), as a founding member, and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), via the U.S.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI participates in almost the entire technical program of both the ISO and the IEC, and administers many key committees and subgroups.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] In many instances, U.S. standards are taken forward to ISO and IEC, through ANSI or the USNC, where they are adopted in whole or in part as international standards.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] Adoption of ISO and IEC standards as American standards increased from 0.2% in 1986 to 15.5% in May 2012.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] Each of the panels works to identify, coordinate, and harmonize voluntary standards relevant to these areas.
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] In 2009, ANSI and the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) formed the Nuclear Energy Standards Coordination Collaborative (NESCC).
[src:mains-electricity/american-national-standards-institute] NESCC is a joint initiative to identify and respond to the current need for standards in the nuclear industry.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] The voltage and frequency of electric power differs between regions.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] In much of the world, a voltage (nominally) of 230 volts and frequency of 50 Hz is used.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] In North America, the most common combination is 120 V and a frequency of 60 Hz.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Other combinations exist, for example, 230 V at 60 Hz.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Travellers' portable appliances may be inoperative or damaged by foreign electrical supplies.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Non-interchangeable plugs and sockets in different regions provide some protection from accidental use of appliances with incompatible voltage and frequency requirements.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] In the US, the electricity that a building receives is called an electrical service, and what comes out of a receptacle is referred to by its voltage, such as 120 or 240.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Sometimes it might be referred to by its number of phases, such as Three Phase.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] In the UK, mains electric power is generally referred to as "the mains".
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] More than half of power in Canada is hydroelectricity, and mains electricity is often referred to as "hydro" in some regions of the country.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] This is also reflected in names of current and historical electricity utilities such as Hydro-Québec, BC Hydro, Manitoba Hydro, Hydro One (Ontario), and Newfoundland and Labrador Hydro.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Worldwide, many different mains power systems are found for the operation of household and light commercial electrical appliances and lighting.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] All of these parameters vary among regions.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] The voltages are generally in the range 100–240 V (always expressed as root-mean-square voltage).
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] The two commonly used frequencies are 50 Hz and 60 Hz.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Single-phase or three-phase power is most commonly used today, although two-phase systems were used early in the 20th century.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Foreign enclaves, such as large industrial plants or overseas military bases, may have a different standard voltage or frequency from the surrounding areas.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Some city areas may use standards different from that of the surrounding countryside (e.g. in Libya).
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Regions in an effective state of anarchy may have no central electrical authority, with electric power provided by incompatible private sources.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Many other combinations of voltage and utility frequency were formerly used, with frequencies between 25 Hz and 133 Hz and voltages from 100 V to 250 V.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Direct current (DC) has been displaced by alternating current (AC) in public power systems, but DC was used especially in some city areas to the end of the 20th century.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] The modern combinations of 230 V/50 Hz and 120 V/60 Hz, listed in IEC 60038, did not apply in the first few decades of the 20th century and are still not universal.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Industrial plants with three-phase power will have different, higher voltages installed for large equipment (and different sockets and plugs), but the common voltages listed here would still be found for lighting and portable equipment.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Electricity is used for lighting, heating, cooling, electric motors and electronic equipment.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Includes televisions, set-top boxes, home theatre systems, DVD players, and video game consoles.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Includes desktop and laptop computers, monitors, and networking equipment.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Includes small electric devices, heating elements, exterior lights, outdoor grills, pool and spa heaters, backup electricity generators, and motors not listed above.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Does not include electric vehicle charging.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Electronic appliances such as computers or televisions sets typically use an AC to DC converter or AC adapter to power the device.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] This is often capable of operation with a wide range of voltage and with both common power frequencies.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Other AC applications usually have much more restricted input ranges.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Portable appliances use single-phase electric power, with two or three wired contacts at each outlet.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Two wires (neutral and live/active/hot) carry current to operate the device.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] A third wire, not always present, connects conductive parts of the appliance case to earth ground.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] This protects users from electric shock if live internal parts accidentally contact the case.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] In northern and central Europe, residential electrical supply is commonly 400 V three-phase electric power, which gives 230 V between any single phase and neutral; house wiring may be a mix of three-phase and single-phase circuits, but three-phase residential use is rare in the UK.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] High-power appliances such as kitchen stoves, water heaters and household power heavy tools like log splitters may be supplied from the 400 V three-phase power supply.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Small portable electrical equipment is connected to the power supply through flexible cables terminated in a plug, which is inserted into a fixed receptacle (socket).
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Larger household electrical equipment and industrial equipment may be permanently wired to the fixed wiring of the building.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] For example, in North American homes a window-mounted self-contained air conditioner unit would be connected to a wall plug, whereas the central air conditioning for a whole home would be permanently wired.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Larger plug and socket combinations are used for industrial equipment carrying larger currents, higher voltages, or three phase electric power.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Circuit breakers and fuses are used to detect short circuits between the line and neutral or ground wires or the drawing of more current than the wires are rated to handle (overload protection) to prevent overheating and possible fire.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] These protective devices are usually mounted in a central panel—most commonly a distribution board or consumer unit—in a building, but some wiring systems also provide a protection device at the socket or within the plug.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Residual-current devices, also known as ground-fault circuit interrupters and appliance leakage current interrupters, are used to detect *ground faults*—flow of current in other than the neutral and line wires (like the ground wire or a person).
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] When a ground fault is detected, the device quickly cuts off the circuit.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] The terms "ground wires" and "earth wires" are used interchangeably, depending on regional differences, for a wire that connects to the earth or some conducting body that serves in place of the earth to take the electrical discharge.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Grounding wires are installed as a safety feature in order to route electricity into another safe body that is not electrically conductive like the air or ground in order to prevent short circuits or electrocution.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Most of the world population (Europe, Africa, Asia, Australia, New Zealand, and much of South America) use a supply that is within 6% of 230 V.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] In the United Kingdom the nominal supply voltage is 230 V +10%/−6% to accommodate the fact that most transformers are in fact still set to 240 V.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] The 230 V standard has become widespread so that 230 V equipment can be used in most parts of the world with the aid of an adapter or a change to the equipment's plug to the standard for the specific country.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] The United States and Canada use a supply voltage of 120 volts ± 6%.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Japan, Taiwan, Saudi Arabia, North America, Central America and some parts of northern South America use a voltage between 100 V and 127 V.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] However, most of the households in Japan equip split-phase electric power like the United States, which can supply 200 V by using reversed phase at the same time.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Brazil is unusual in having both 127 V and 220 V systems at 60 Hz and also permitting interchangeable plugs and sockets.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Saudi Arabia and Mexico have mixed voltage systems; in residential and light commercial buildings both countries use 127 volts, with 220 volts at 60 Hz in commercial and industrial applications.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] The Saudi government approved plans in August 2010 to transition the country to a totally 230/400-volt 60 Hz system.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] A distinction should be made between the voltage at the point of supply (nominal voltage at the point of interconnection between the electrical utility and the user) and the voltage rating of the equipment (utilization or load voltage).
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] Typically the utilization voltage is 3% to 5% lower than the nominal system voltage; for example, a nominal 208 V supply system will be connected to motors with "200 V" on their nameplates.
[src:mains-electricity/mains-electricity] This allows for the voltage drop between equipment and supply.
